obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line 9
  line `CHAPTER II`
  line `C ONSTITUTION OF THE F ORCE AND CONDITIONS OF SERVICE OF THE MEMBERS OF THE F ORCE`
  line `4. Constitution of the Force. — ( 1 ) There shall be an armed force of the Union called the`
  line `Indo - Tibetan Border Police Force for ensuring the security of the borders of India and performing such`
  line `other duties as may be entrusted t o it by the Central Government.`
  line `( 2 ) Subject to the provisions of this Act, the Force shall be constituted in such manner as may be`
  line `prescribed and the conditions of service of the members of the Force shall be such as may be prescribed.`
  line `5. Control, direction, etc. — ( 1 ) The general superintendence, direction and control of the Force shall`
  line `vest in, and be exercised by, the Central Government and subject thereto, and to the provisions of this Act`
  line `and the rules, the command and supervision of the Force shall vest in an officer to be appointed by the`
  line `Central Government as the Director - General of the Force.`
  line `( 2 ) The Director - General shall, in the discharge of his duties under this Act, be assisted by such`
  line `number of Additional Directors - General, Inspectors - General, Deputy Inspectors - General, Additional`
  line `Deputy Inspectors - General, Commandants and other officers as may be appointed by the Ce ntral`
  line Government.
  line `6. Enrolment. — The persons to be enrolled to the Force, the mode of enrolment, and the procedure`
  line `for enrolment shal l be such as may be prescribed.`
  line `7. Liability for service outside India. — Every member of the Force shall be liable to serve in any`
  line `part of In dia as well as outside India.`
  line `8. Resignation and withdrawal from the pos t. — No member of t he Force shall be at liberty, —`
  line `( a ) to resign his appointment during the term of his engagement; or`
  line `( b ) to withdraw himself from all or any o f the duties of his appointment,`
  line `except with the previous permission in writi ng of the prescribed authority.`
  line `9. Tenure of service under the Act. — Every person subject to this Act shall hold office during the`
  line `pleasure of the President.`
  line `10. Termination of service by Central Government. — Subject to the provisions of this Act and the`
  line `rules, the Central Government may dismiss or remove from the service any p erson subject to this Act.`
  line `11. Dismissal, removal or reduction by the Director - General and by other officers. — ( 1 ) The`
  line `Director - Ge neral, any Additional Director - General or Inspector - General may dismiss or remove from the`
  line `service or reduce to a lower grade or rank or ranks any person subject to this Act other than an officer.`
  line `( 2 ) An officer not below the rank of Additional Deputy Inspector - General or any prescribed officer`
  line `may dismiss or remove from the service any person under his command other than an officer or a`
  line `subordinate officer of such rank or ranks as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 3 ) Any such officer as is mentioned in sub - section ( 2 ) may reduce to a lower grade or rank or ranks`
  line `any person under his command except an of ficer or a subordinate officer.`
  line `( 4 ) The exercise of any power under this section shall be subject to the provisions of this Act and the`
  line rules.
  line `12. Certificate of termination of service. — A subordinate officer, or an under - officer or other`
  line `enrolled person who is retired, discharged, released, removed or dismissed from the service shall be`
  line `furnished by the officer, to whose command he is subject, with a certificate in Hindi or English language`
  line `setting forth —`
  line `( a ) the aut hority terminating his service;`
  line `( b ) the cause for such termination; and`
  line `( c ) the full peri od of his service in the Force.`
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_10:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-10
  sectionNo (10)
  orderNo 10
  title `Page 10`
  content obj_root_law_sections_10_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes
  sourcePage 10
obj_root_law_sections_10_content:
  string
  line 10
  line `13. Restrictions respecting right to form association, freedom of speech, etc. — ( 1 ) No person`
  line `subject to this Act shall, without the previous sanction in writing of the Central Government or of the`
  line `prescribed authority, —`
  line `( a ) be a member of, or be associated in any way with, any trade union, labour union, political`
  line `association or with any class of trade unions, labour unions or political associations; or`
  line `( b ) be a member of, or be associated in any way with, any society, institution, association or`
  line `organisation that is not recognised as part of the Force or is not of a purely social, recre ational or`
  line `religious nature; or`
  line `( c ) communicate with the press or publish or cause to be published any book, letter or other`
  line `document except where such communication or publication is in the bona fide discharge of his duties`
  line `or is of a purely literary, artistic or scientific characte r or is of a prescribed nature.`
  line `Explanation. — If any question arises as to whether any society, institution, association or organisation`
  line `is of a purely social, recreational or religious nature under clause ( b ) of this sub - section, the decision of`
  line `the Central Gov ernment thereon shall be final.`
  line `( 2 ) No person subject to this Act shall participate in, or address, any meeting or take part in any`
  line `demonstration organised by anybody of persons for any political purposes or for such other purposes as`
  line `may be prescribed.`
  line `14. Remedy of aggrieved persons other than officers. — ( 1 ) Any person subject to this Act other`
  line `than an officer who deems himself wronged by any superior or other officer may complain to the officer`
  line `und er whose command he is serving.`
  line `( 2 ) When the officer complained against is the officer to whom any complaint should, under`
  line `sub - section ( 1 ), be preferred, the aggrieved person may complain to such officer ’ s next superior officer.`
  line `( 3 ) Every officer receiving any such complaint shall make as complete an investigation into it as may`
  line `be possible for giving full redress to the complainant, or when necessary, refer the com plaint to a superior`
  line authority.
  line `( 4 ) The Director - General may revise any decision made under any of the foregoing sub - sections, but,`
  line `subject thereto, such decision shall be final.`
  line `15. Remedy of aggrieved officers. — Any officer who deems himself wronged by his commanding`
  line `officer or any other superior officer and who, on due application made to his commanding officer or such`
  line `other superior officer, does not receive the redress to which he considers himself entitled, may complain`
  line `to the Director - General or the Central Gov ernment through proper channel.`
  line `CHAPTER III`
  line `O FFENCES`
  line `16. Offences in relation to the enemy or terrorist and punishable with death. — Any person`
  line `subject to this Act who commits any of the following offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) shamefully abandons or delivers up any post, place or guard, committed to his charge or`
  line `whi ch it is his duty to defend; or`
  line `( b ) intentionally uses any means to compel or induce any person subject to this Act or to any`
  line `other law relating to military, naval, air force or any other armed force of the Union to abstain from`
  line `acting against the enemy or to discourage such person from acting again st the enemy; or`
  line `( c ) in the presence of the enemy o r terrorist, shamefully casts away his arms, ammunition, tools`
  line `or equipment or misbehaves in such manner as to show cowardice; or`
  line `( d ) treacherously holds correspondence with, or communicates intelligence to, the enemy,`
  line `terrorist or any perso n in arms against the Union; or`
  line `( e ) directly or indirectly assists the enemy or terrorist with money, arms ammunition, stores or`
  line `supplies or in any other manner whatsoever; or`
obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_11:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-11
  sectionNo (11)
  orderNo 11
  title `Page 11`
  content obj_root_law_sections_11_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes
  sourcePage 11
obj_root_law_sections_11_content:
  string
  line 11
  line `( f ) in time of active operation against the enemy or terrorist, intentionally occasions a false alarm`
  line `in action, camp, quarters or spreads or causes to be spread reports calculated to create alarm or`
  line `despondency; or`
  line `( g ) in time of action leaves his commanding officer or other superior officer or his post, guard,`
  line `picket, patrol or party without being regularly relieved or without leave; or`
  line `( h ) having been captured by the enemy or made a prisoner of war, voluntarily se rves with or aids`
  line `the enemy; or`
  line `( i ) k nowingly harbours or protects an enemy, not being a prisoner; or`
  line `( j ) being a sentry in time of active operation against the enemy or alarm, sleeps upon his post or is`
  line `intoxicated; or`
  line `( k ) knowingly does any act calculated to imperil the success of the Force or the military, naval or`
  line `air force of India or any forces co - operating therewith or any part of such forces,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer death or such less punishment as is in this Act`
  line mentioned.
  line `17. Offences in relation to the enemy and not punishable with death. — Any person subject to this`
  line `Act who commits any of the following offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) is taken prisoner or captured by the enemy, by want of due precaution or through`
  line `disobedience of orders, or wilful neglect of duty, or having been taken prisoner or so captured fails to`
  line `rejoin his service when able to do so; or`
  line `( b ) without due authority holds correspondence with, or communicates intelligence to, the enemy`
  line `or any person in league with the enemy or having come by the knowledge of any such`
  line `correspondence or communication, wilfully omits to discover it immediately to his commanding`
  line `off icer or other superior officer,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `fourteen years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `18. Offences punishable more severely on active duty than at other times. — Any person subject to`
  line `this Act who commits any of the following offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) forces a safeguard, or forces or uses criminal force to a sentry; or`
  line `( b ) breaks into any house or other place in search of plunder; or`
  line `( c ) being a sentry sleeps upon h is post, or is intoxicated; or`
  line `( d ) without orders from his superior officer leaves his gu ard, picket, patrol or post; or`
  line `( e ) intentionally or through neglect occasions a false alarm in camp or quarters, or spreads or`
  line `causes to be spread reports calculated to create unnec essary alarm or despondency; or`
  line `( f ) makes known the parole, watchward or countersign to any person not entitled to receive it; or`
  line `knowingly gives a parole, watchward or a countersign d ifferent from what he received,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, —`
  line `( i ) if he commits any such offence when on active duty, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a`
  line `term which may extend to fourteen years or such less punishment a s is in this Act mentioned; and`
  line `( ii ) if he commits any such offence when not on active duty, be liable to suffer imprisonment for`
  line `a term which may extend to seven years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `19. Mutiny. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the foll owing offences, that is to`
  line `say, —`
  line `( a ) begins, incites, causes or conspires with any other person to cause any mutiny in the Force or`
  line `in the military, naval or air force of India or any fo rces co - operating therewith; or`
  line `( b ) joins in any such mutiny; or`
obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_12:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-12
  sectionNo (12)
  orderNo 12
  title `Page 12`
  content obj_root_law_sections_12_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes
  sourcePage 12
obj_root_law_sections_12_content:
  string
  line 12
  line `( c ) being present at any such mutiny, does not use his utmost ende avours to suppress the same; or`
  line `( d ) knowing or having reason to believe in the existence of any such mutiny, or of any intent ion`
  line `to mutiny or of any such conspiracy, does not, without delay, give information thereof to his`
  line `commanding office r or other superior officer; or`
  line `( e ) endeavours to seduce any person in the Force or in the military, naval or air force of India or`
  line `any forces co - operating therewith from his d uty or allegiance to the Union,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer death or such less punishment as is in this Act`
  line mentioned.
  line `20. Desertion and aiding desertion. — ( 1 ) Any person subject to this Act who deserts or attempts to`
  line `desert the service shall, on conviction by a Force Court, —`
  line `( a ) if he commits the offence when on active duty or when under orders for active duty, be liable`
  line `to suffer death or such less punishment a s is in this Act mentioned; and`
  line `( b ) if he commits the offence under any other circumstances, be liable to suffer imprisonment for`
  line `a term which may extend to seven years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person subject to this Act who knowingly harbours any such deserter shall, on conviction by`
  line `a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to seven years or such less`
  line `punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `( 3 ) Any person subject to this Act who, being cognizant of any desertion or attempt at desertion of a`
  line `person subject to this Act, does not forthwith give notice to his own or some other superior officer, or take`
  line `any steps in his power to cause such person to be apprehended, shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be`
  line `liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to two years or such less punishme nt as is in`
  line `this Act mentioned.`
  line `( 4 ) For the purposes o f this Act, a person deserts, —`
  line `( a ) if he absents from his unit or the place of duty at any time with the intention of not reporting`
  line `back to such unit or place, or who, at any time and under any circumstances when absent from his`
  line `unit or place of duty, does any act which shows that he has an intention of not reporting to such unit`
  line `or place of duty;`
  line `( b ) if he absents himself without leave with intent to avoid any active duty.`
  line `21. Absence without leave. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the follow ing`
  line `offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) ab sents himself without leave; or`
  line `( b ) without sufficient cause ove rstays leave granted to him; or`
  line `( c ) being on leave of absence and having received information from the appropriate authority that`
  line `any battalion or part thereof or any other unit of the Force, to which he belongs, has been ordered on`
  line `active duty, fails, without sufficient cau se, to rejoin without delay; or`
  line `( d ) without sufficient cause fails to appear at the time fixed at the parade or place appointed for`
  line `exercise or duty; or`
  line `( e ) when on parade, or on the line of march, without sufficient cause or without leave from his`
  line `superior officer, quits the parade or line of march; or`
  line `( f ) w hen in camp or elsewhere, is found beyond any limits fixed, or in any place prohibited, by`
  line `any general, local or other order, without a pass or written leav e from his superior officer; or`
  line `( g ) without leave from his superior officer or without due cause, absents himself from any school`
  line `or training institution when duly ordered to attend there,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `three years or such less punishment as is in th is Act mentioned.`
obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_13:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-13
  sectionNo (13)
  orderNo 13
  title `Page 13`
  content obj_root_law_sections_13_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes
  sourcePage 13
obj_root_law_sections_13_content:
  string
  line 13
  line `22. Striking or threatening superior officers. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of`
  line `the follow ing offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) uses criminal force to or assaults his superior officer; or`
  line `( b ) uses threateni ng language to such officer; or`
  line `( c ) uses insubordinate language to such officer,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, —`
  line `( i ) if such officer is at the time in the execution of his office or, if the offence is committed on`
  line `active duty, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to fourteen years or such`
  line `less punishment a s is in this Act mentioned; and`
  line `( ii ) in other cases, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to ten years or`
  line `such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned:`
  line `Provided that in the case of an offence specified in clause ( c ) the imprisonme nt shall not exceed`
  line `five years.`
  line `23. Disobedience to superior officer. — ( 1 ) Any person subject to this Act who disobeys in such`
  line `manner as to show a wilful defiance of authority any lawful command given personally by his superior`
  line `officer in the execution of his office whether the same is given orally, or in writing or by signal or`
  line `otherwise, shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may`
  line `extend to fourteen years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person subject to this Act who disobeys any lawful command given by his superior officer`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, —`
  line `( a ) if he commits such offence when on active duty, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term`
  line `which may extend to fourte e n years or such less punishment a s is in this Act mentioned; and`
  line `( b ) if he commits such offence when not on active duty, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a`
  line `term which may extend to five years or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `24. Insubordination and obstruction. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the`
  line `follow ing offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) being concerned in any quarrel, affray or disorder, refuses to obey any officer, though of`
  line `inferior rank, who orders him into arrest, or uses criminal force to, or assaults, any such officer; or`
  line `( b ) uses criminal force to, or assaults, any person, whether subject to this Act or not, in whose`
  line `custody he is lawfully placed, and whether he is or is not his superior officer; or`
  line `( c ) resists an escort whose duty it is to apprehend him or to have him in charge; or`
  line `( d ) breaks out of barracks, camp or quarters; or`
  line `( e ) neglects to obey any general, local or other order; or`
  line `( f ) impedes the Force Police referred to in section 75 or any person lawfully acting on his behalf,`
  line `or when called upon, refuses to assist in the execution of his duty a Force Police or any person`
  line `lawfully acting on his behalf,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend, in`
  line `the case of the offences specified in clauses ( d ) and ( e ), to two years, and in the case of the offences`
  line `specified in the other clauses, to ten years, or in either case such less punishment as is in this Act`
  line mentioned.
  line `25. False answers on enrolment. — Any person having become subject to this Act who is discovered`
  line `to have made at the time of enrolment a wilfully false answer to any question set forth in the prescribed`
  line `form of enrolment which has been put to him by the enrolling officer before whom he appears for the`
  line `purpose of being enrolled, shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a`
  line `term which may extend to five years or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_14:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-14
  sectionNo (14)
  orderNo 14
  title `Page 14`
  content obj_root_law_sections_14_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes
  sourcePage 14
obj_root_law_sections_14_content:
  string
  line 14
  line `26. Unbecoming conduct. — Any officer or subordinate officer who behaves in a manner`
  line `unbecoming of his position and the character expected of him shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be`
  line `liable to be dismissed or to suffer such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `27. Certain forms of disgraceful conduct. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the`
  line `follo wing offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) is guilty of any disgraceful conduct of a cruel, indecent or unnatural kind; or`
  line `( b ) malingers or feigns or produces disease or infirmity in himself or intentionally delays his cure`
  line `or aggravat es his disease or infirmity; or`
  line `( c ) with intent to render himself or any other person unfit for service, voluntarily causes hurt to`
  line `himself or that person,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `seven years or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `28. Ill - treating a subordinate. — Any officer, subordinate officer or under - officer, who uses criminal`
  line `force to, or otherwise ill - treats, any person subject to this Act, being his subordinate in rank or position,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `seven years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `29. Intoxication. — ( 1 ) Any person subject to this Act who is found in a state of intoxication, whether`
  line `on duty or not, shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which`
  line `may extend to six months or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `( 2 ) For the purposes of sub - section ( 1 ), a person shall be deemed to be in a state of intoxication if,`
  line `owing to the influence of alcohol or any drug whether alone, or any combination with any other`
  line `substance, he is unfit to be entrusted with his duty or with any duty which he may be called upon to`
  line `perform or, behaves in a disorderly manner or in a manner likely to bring discredi t to the Force.`
  line `30. Permitting escape of person in custody. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of`
  line `the foll owing offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) when in command of a guard, picket, patrol, detachment or post, releases without proper`
  line `authority, whether wilfully or without reasonable excuse, any person committed to his charge, or`
  line `refuses to receive any pris oner or person so committed; or`
  line `( b ) wilfully or without reasonable excuse allows to escape any person who is committed to his`
  line `charge, or whom i t is his duty to keep or guard,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable, if he has acted wilfully, to suffer imprisonment for a term`
  line `which may extend to ten years or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned; and if he has not acted`
  line `wilfully, to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to two years or such less punishme nt as is`
  line `in this Act mentioned.`
  line `31. Irregularity in connection with arrest or confinement. — Any person subject to this Act who`
  line `commits any of the following offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) unnecessarily detains a person in arrest or confinement without bringing him to trial, or fails`
  line `to bring his case before the proper authority for investigation; or`
  line `( b ) having committed a person to Force custody fails without reasonable cause to deliver at the`
  line `time of such committal, or as soon as p racticable, and in any case within forty - eight hours thereafter,`
  line `to the officer or other person into whose custody the person arrested is committed, an account in`
  line `writing signed by himself of the offence with which the person so committed is charged,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `one year or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `32. Escape from custody. — Any person subject to this Act who, being in lawful custody, escapes or`
  line `attempts to escape, shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term`
  line `which may extend to three years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_15:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-15
  sectionNo (15)
  orderNo 15
  title `Page 15`
  content obj_root_law_sections_15_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes
  sourcePage 15
obj_root_law_sections_15_content:
  string
  line 15
  line `33. Offences in respect of property. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the following`
  line `offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) commits theft of any property belonging to the Government, or to any Force mess, band or`
  line `institution, or to any person subject to this Act; or`
  line `( b ) dishonestly misappropriates or converts to his own use any such property; or`
  line `( c ) commits criminal breach of trust in r espect of any such property; or`
  line `( d ) dishonestly receives or retains any such property in respect of which any of the offences under`
  line `clauses ( a ), ( b ) and ( c ) has been committed, knowing or having reason to believe the commission of`
  line `such off ence; or`
  line `( e ) wilfully destroys or injures any property of the Government entrusted to him; or`
  line `( f ) does any other thing with intent to defraud, or to cause wrongful gain to one person or`
  line `wrongful loss to another person,`
  line `s hall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to ten`
  line `years or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `3 4. Extortion and exaction. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the following`
  line `off ences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) commits extortion; o r`
  line `( b ) without proper authority exacts from any person money, provisions or service,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extent to ten`
  line `years or such less punishment as in this Act mentioned.`
  line `35. Making away with equipment. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the`
  line `following offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) makes away with, or is concerned in making away with, any arms, ammunition, equipment,`
  line `instruments, tools, clothing or any other thing being the property of the Government issued to him for`
  line `his use or entrusted to him; or`
  line `( b ) loses by neglect anyth ing mentioned in clause ( a ); or`
  line `( c ) sells, pawns, destroys or defaces any medal or decoration granted to him,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend, in`
  line `the case of the offences specified in clause ( a ), to ten years, and in the case of the offences specified in the`
  line `other clauses, to five years, or in either case such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `36. Injury to property. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the following offences,`
  line `that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) destroys or injures any property mentioned in clause ( a ) of section 35, or any property`
  line `belonging to any Force mess, band or institution, or to any person subject to this Act; or`
  line `( b ) commits any act which causes damage to, or destruction of, any propert y of the Government`
  line `by fire; or`
  line `( c ) kills, injures, makes away with, ill - t r eats or loses any, animal entrusted to him,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable, if he has acted wilfully, to suffer imprisonment for a term`
  line `which may extend to ten years or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned; and if he has acted`
  line `without reasonable excuse, to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to five years or such less`
  line `punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_16:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-16
  sectionNo (16)
  orderNo 16
  title `Page 16`
  content obj_root_law_sections_16_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes
  sourcePage 16
obj_root_law_sections_16_content:
  string
  line 16
  line `37. False accusations. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the follow ing offences,`
  line `that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) makes a false accusation against any person subject to this Act, knowing or having reason to`
  line `believe such accusation to be false; or`
  line `( b ) in making a complaint against any person subject to this Act makes any statement affecting`
  line `the character of such person, knowing or having reason to believe such statement to be false, or`
  line `knowingly and wilfully suppresses any material facts,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `three years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `38. Falsifying official documents and false declarations. — Any person subject to this Act who`
  line `commits any of the following offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) in any report, return, list, certificate, book or other document made or signed by him, or of the`
  line `contents of which it is his duty to ascertain the accuracy, knowingly makes, or is privy to the making`
  line `of, any fa lse or fraudulent statement; or`
  line `( b ) in any document of the description mentioned in clause ( a ) knowingly makes, or is privy to`
  line `the making of, any omiss ion, with intent to defraud; or`
  line `( c ) knowingly and with intent to injure any person, or knowingly and with intent to defraud,`
  line `suppresses, defaces, alters or makes away with any document which it is his duty to preserve or`
  line `produ ce; or`
  line `( d ) where it is his official duty to make a declaration respecting any matter, knowingly makes a`
  line `false declaration; or`
  line `( e ) obtains for himself, or for any other person, any pension, allowance or other advantage or`
  line `privilege by a statement which is false, and which he either knows or believes to be false or does not`
  line `believe to be true, or by making or using a false entry in any book or record, or by making any`
  line `document containing a false statement, or by omitting to make a true entry or document containing a`
  line `true statement,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to ten`
  line `years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `39. Signing in blank and failure to report. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the`
  line `following offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) when signing any document relating to pay, arms, ammunition, equipment, clothing, supplies`
  line `or stores, or any property of the Government fraudulently leaves in blank any material part for which`
  line `his signature is a voucher; or`
  line `( b ) refuses or by culpable neglect omits to make or send a report or return which it is his duty to`
  line `make or send,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `three years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `40. Offences relating to Force Court. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the`
  line `following offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) being duly summoned or ordered to attend as a witness before a Force Court, wilfully or`
  line `without reasonable excuse, makes default in attending; or`
  line `( b ) refuses to take an oath or make an affirmation legally required by a Force Court to be taken or`
  line `made; or`
  line `( c ) refuses to produce or deliver any document in his power or control legally required by a Force`
  line `Court to be produced or delivered by him; or`
  line `( d ) refuses, when a witness, to answer any question which he is by law bound to answer; or`
obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_17:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-17
  sectionNo (17)
  orderNo 17
  title `Page 17`
  content obj_root_law_sections_17_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes
  sourcePage 17
obj_root_law_sections_17_content:
  string
  line 17
  line `( e ) is guilty of contempt of the Force Court by using insulting or threatening language, or by`
  line `causing any interruption or disturbance in the proceedings of such Court,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `three years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `41. False evidence. — Any person subject to this Act who, having been duly sworn or affirmed before`
  line `any Force Court or other court competent under this Act to administer an oath or affirmation, makes any`
  line `statement which is false, and which he either knows or believes to be false or does not believe to be true,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `seven years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `42. Unlawful detention of pay. — Any officer, subordinate officer or under - officer who, having`
  line `received the pay of a person subject to this Act unlawfully detains or refuses to pay the same when due,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `five years or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `43. Violation of good order and discipline. — Any person subject to this Act who is guilty of any act`
  line `or omission which, though not specified in this Act, is prejudicial to good order and discipline of the`
  line `Force shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend`
  line `to seven years or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `44. Miscel l aneous offences. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any of the following`
  line `offences, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) being in command at any post or on the march, and receiving a complaint that any one under`
  line `his c ommand has beaten or other wise maltreated or oppressed any person, or has disturbed any fair or`
  line `market, or committed any riot or trespass, fails to have due reparation made to the injured person or to`
  line `report the c ase to the proper authority; or`
  line `( b ) by defiling any place of worship, or otherwise, intentionally insults the religion, or wounds the`
  line `relig ious feelings of any person; or`
  line `( c ) attempts to commit suicide, and in such attempt does any act towards the commission of such`
  line `offence; or`
  line `( d ) being below the rank of subordinate officer, when off duty, appears without proper authority,`
  line `in or about camp, or in or about, or when going to, or returning from, any town or bazar, carrying a`
  line `rifle, swor d or other offensive weapon; or`
  line `( e ) directly or indirectly accepts or obtains, or agrees to accept, or attempts to obtain, for himself`
  line `or for any other person, any gratification as a motive or reward for procuring the enrolment of any`
  line `person, or leave of absence, promotion or any other advantage or indulgence fo r any person in the`
  line `service; or`
  line `( f ) commits any offence against the property or person of any inhabitant of, or resident in, the`
  line `country in which he is serving,`
  line `shall, on conviction by a Force Court, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `seven years or such less punishment as is in t his Act mentioned.`
  line `45. Attempt. — Any person subject to this Act who attempts to commit any of the offences specified`
  line `in sections 16 to 44 (both inclusive) and in such attempt does any act towards the commission of the`
  line `offence shall, on conviction by a Force Court, where no express provision is made by this Act for the`
  line `punishme nt of such attempt, be liable, —`
  line `( a ) if the offence attempted to be committed is punishable with death, to suffer imprisonment for`
  line `a term which may extend to fourteen years or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned; and`
  line `( b ) if the offence attempted to be committed is punishable with imprisonment, to suffer`
  line `imprisonment for a term which may extend to one - half of the longest term provided for that offence`
  line `or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_18:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-18
  sectionNo (18)
  orderNo 18
  title `Page 18`
  content obj_root_law_sections_18_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes
  sourcePage 18
obj_root_law_sections_18_content:
  string
  line 18
  line `46. Abetment of offences that have been committed. — Any person subject to this Act who abets the`
  line `commission of any of the offences specified in sections 16 to 44 (both inclusive) shall, on conviction by a`
  line `Force Court, if the act abetted is committed in consequence of the abetment and no express provision is`
  line `made by this Act for the punishment of such abetment, be liable to suffer the punishment provided for`
  line `that offence or such less punishme nt as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `47. Abetment of offences punishable with death and not c ommitt e d. — Any person subject to this`
  line `Act who abets the commission of any of the offences punishable with death under sections 16, 19 and`
  line `sub - section ( 1 ) of section 20 shall, on conviction by a Force Court, if that offence be not committed in`
  line `consequence of the abetment, and no express provision is made by this Act for the punishment of such`
  line `abetment, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to fourteen years or such less`
  line `punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `48. Abetment of offences punishable with imprisonment and not committed. — Any person`
  line `subject to this Act who abets the commission of any of the offences specified in sections 16 to 44 (both`
  line `inclusive) and punishable with imprisonment shall, on conviction by a Force Court, if that offence be not`
  line `committed in consequence of the abetment, and no express provision is made by this Act for the`
  line `punishment of such abetment, be liable to suffer imprisonment for a term which may extend to one - half of`
  line `the longest term provided for that offence or such less punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `49. Civil offences. — Subject to the provisions of section 50, any person subject to this Act who at any`
  line `place in, or beyond, India commits any civil offence shall be deemed to be guilty of an offence against`
  line `this Act and, if charged therewith under this section shall be liable to be tried by a Force Court and, on`
  line `conviction, be punishable as follows, that is t o say, —`
  line `( a ) if the offence is one which would be punishable under any law in force in India with death, he`
  line `shall be liable to suffer any punishment, assigned for the offence, by the aforesaid law and such less`
  line `punishment a s is in this Act mentioned; and`
  line `( b ) in any other case, he shall be liable to suffer any punishment, assigned for the offence by the`
  line `law in force in India, or imprisonment for a term which may extend to seven years, or such less`
  line `punishment as is in this Act mentioned.`
  line `50. Civil offences not triable by a Force Court. — A person subject to this Act who commits an`
  line `offence of murder or culpable homicide not amounting to murder against, or of rape in relation to, a`
  line `person not subject to this Act shall not be deemed to be guilty of an offence against this Act and shall not`
  line `be tried by a Force Court, unless he commits any of the said offences —`
  line `( a ) while on active duty; or`
  line `( b ) at any place outside India; or`
  line `( c ) at any place specified by the Central Government by notification, in this behalf.`
  line `C HAPTER IV`
  line `P UNISHMENTS`
  line `51. Punishment awardable by Force Courts. — ( 1 ) Punishments may be inflicted in respect of`
  line `offences committed by persons subject to this Act and convicted by Force Courts according to the scale`
  line `following, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) death;`
  line `( b ) imprisonment which may be for the term of life or any other lesser term but excluding`
  line `imprisonment for a term not exceeding three months in Force custody;`
  line `( c ) dismiss al or removal from the service;`
  line `( d ) compulso ry retirement from the service;`
  line `( e ) imprisonment for a term not exceeding three months in Force custody;`
obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_19:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-19
  sectionNo (19)
  orderNo 19
  title `Page 19`
  content obj_root_law_sections_19_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes
  sourcePage 19
obj_root_law_sections_19_content:
  string
  line 19
  line `( f ) reduction to the ranks or to a lower rank or grade or a place in the list of their rank in the case`
  line `of an under - officer;`
  line `( g ) reduction to next lower rank in case of an officer or subordinate officer:`
  line `Provided that no officer shall be reduced to a rank lower than the one to wh ich he was initially`
  line appointed;
  line `( h ) forfeiture of seniority of rank and forfeiture of all or any part of the servic e for the purpose of`
  line promotion;
  line `( i ) forfeiture of service for the purpo se of increased pay or pension;`
  line `( j ) fine, in respect of civil offences;`
  line `( k ) severe reprimand or reprimand except in the case of persons below the rank of an`
  line `under - officer;`
  line `( l ) forfeiture of pay and allowances for a period not exceeding three months for an of fence`
  line `committed on active duty;`
  line `( m ) forfeiture in the case of person sentenced to dismissal from the service of all arrears of pay`
  line `and allowances and other public money due to him at the time of such dismissal;`
  line `( n ) stoppage of pay and allowances until any proved loss or damage occasioned by the offence for`
  line `whic h he is convicted is made good.`
  line `( 2 ) Each of the punishments specified in sub - section ( 1 ) shall be deemed to be inferior in degree to`
  line `every punishment p receding it in the above scale.`
  line `52. Alternative punishments awardable by Force Courts. — Subject to the provisions of this Act, a`
  line `Force Court may, on convicting a person subject to this Act of any of the offences specified in sections 16`
  line `to 48 (both inclusive) award either the particular punishment with which the offence is stated in the said`
  line `sections to be punishable or, in lieu thereof, any one of the punishments lower in the scale set out in`
  line `section 51 regard being had to the na ture and degree of the offence.`
  line `53. Combination of punishments. — A Force Court may award in addition to, or without, any other`
  line `punishment, the punishment specified in clause ( c ) of sub - section ( 1 ) of section 51, or any one or more of`
  line `the punishments specified in clauses ( f ) to ( n ) (both inclusive) of that sub - section.`
  line `54. Retention in the force of a person convicted on active duty. — When on active duty an enrolled`
  line `person has been sentenced by a Force Court to imprisonment whether combined with dismissal or not, the`
  line `prescribed officer may direct that such person may be retained to serve in the ranks, and such service shall`
  line `be reckoned as pa rt of his term of imprisonment.`
  line `55. Punishments otherwise than by Force Courts. — Punishments may also be inflicted in respect`
  line `of offences committed by persons subject to this Act without the intervention of a Force Court in the`
  line `manner stated in sections 56, 58 and 59.`
  line `56. Minor punishments. — ( 1 ) Subject to the provisions of section 57, a commanding officer of and`
  line `above the rank of Commandant may, in the prescribed manner, proceed against a person subject to this`
  line `Act, other than an officer or a subordinate officer, who is charged with an offence under this Act and`
  line `award such person, to the extent prescribed, one or more of the following punishments, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) imprisonment in Force c ustody up to twenty - eight days;`
  line `( b ) det ention up to twenty - eight days;`
  line `( c ) confinement to the lines up to twenty - eight days;`
  line `( d ) extra guards or duties;`
  line `( e ) deprivation of any special position or special emoluments or any acting rank;`
  line `( f ) severe reprimand or reprimand;`
obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_20:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-20
  sectionNo (20)
  orderNo 20
  title `Page 20`
  content obj_root_law_sections_20_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes
  sourcePage 20
obj_root_law_sections_20_content:
  string
  line 20
  line `( g ) fine up to fourt een days ’ pay in any one month;`
  line `( h ) deductions from his pay and allowances of any sum required to make good any loss or`
  line `damage occasioned by the of fence for which he is punished.`
  line `( 2 ) If any unit, training centre or other establishment of the Force is being temporarily commanded by`
  line `an officer of the rank of Second - in - Command or Deputy Commandant, such officer shall have full powers`
  line `of a commanding office r specified in sub - section ( 1 ).`
  line `( 3 ) Subject to the provisions of section 57, a Deputy Commandant or an Assistant Commandant,`
  line `commanding a company or a detachment or an outpost, shall have the power to proceed against a person`
  line `subject to this Act, other than an officer or a subordinate officer, who is charged with an offence under`
  line `this Act and award such person to the extent prescribed, one or more of the punishments specified in`
  line `clauses ( a ) to ( d ) and ( h ) of sub - section ( 1 ) provided that the maximum limit of punishment awarded`
  line `under each of the clauses ( a ), ( b ) and ( c ) shall not exceed fourteen days.`
  line `( 4 ) A subordinate officer not below the rank of Sub - Inspector who is commanding a detachment or an`
  line `outpost shall have the powers to proceed against a person subject to this Act, other than a subordinate`
  line `officer or an under - officer, who is charged with an offence under this Act and award such person to the`
  line `extent prescribed, one or more of the punishment s specified under clauses ( c ) and ( d ) of sub - section ( 1 )`
  line `provided that the maximum limit of punishment awarded under clause ( c ) shall not exceed fourteen days.`
  line `57. Limit of punishments under section 56. — ( 1 ) In the case of an award of two or more of the`
  line `punishments specified in clauses ( a ), ( b ), ( c ) and ( d ) of sub - section ( 1 ) of section 56, the punishments`
  line `specified in clause ( c ) or clause ( d ) shall take effect only at the end of the punishment specifi ed in`
  line `clause ( a ) or clause ( b ).`
  line `( 2 ) When two or more of the punishments specified in clauses ( a ), ( b ) and ( c ) of sub - section ( 1 ) of`
  line `section 56 are awarded to a person conjointly, or when already undergoing one or more of the said`
  line `punishments, the whole extent of the punishments shall not exceed in the aggregate forty - two days.`
  line `( 3 ) The punishments specified in c lauses ( a ), ( b ) and ( c ) of sub - section ( 1 ) of section 56 shall not be`
  line `awarded to any person who is of the rank of an under - officer or was, at the time of committing the`
  line `offence for which he is punished, of s uch rank.`
  line `( 4 ) The punishment specified in clause ( f ) of sub - section ( 1 ) of section 56 shall not be awarded to any`
  line `person belo w the rank of an under - officer.`
  line `58. Punishment of persons of or below the rank of Commandant by Inspectors - General and`
  line `others. — ( 1 ) An officer not below the rank of Inspector - General may, in the prescribed manner, proceed`
  line `against an officer of or below the rank of Commandant who is charged with an offence under this Act and`
  line `award one or more of the following punishments, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) forfeiture of seniority, or in the case of any of them whose promotion depends upon length of`
  line `service, forfeiture of service for the purpose of promotion for a period not exceeding one year, but`
  line `subject to the right of the accused previous to the award to elec t to be tried by a Force Court;`
  line `( b ) severe reprimand or reprimand;`
  line `( c ) deduction from pay and allowances of any sum required to make good any proved loss or`
  line `damage occasioned by the of fence of which he is convicted.`
  line `( 2 ) An officer not below the rank of Additional Deputy Inspector - General may, in the prescribed`
  line `manner, proceed against a person of or below the rank of Subedar - Major who is charged with an offence`
  line `under this Act and award one or more of the following punishments, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) forfeiture of seniority, or in the case of any of them whose promotion depends upon the length`
  line `of service, forfeiture of service for the purpose of promotion for a period not exceeding one year, but`
  line `subject to the right of the accused previous to the award to elec t to be tried by a Force Court;`
  line `( b ) severe reprimand or reprimand;`
obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_21:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-21
  sectionNo (21)
  orderNo 21
  title `Page 21`
  content obj_root_law_sections_21_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes
  sourcePage 21
obj_root_law_sections_21_content:
  string
  line 21
  line `( c ) deduction from pay and allowances of any sum required to make good any proved loss or`
  line `damage occasioned by the of fence of which he is convicted.`
  line `( 3 ) An officer not below the rank of Commandant may, in the prescribed manner, proceed against a`
  line `person of or below the rank of Subedar - Major who is charged with an offence under this Act and award`
  line `any one or both of the following punishments, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) severe reprimand or reprimand;`
  line `( b ) deduction from pay and allowances of any sum required to make good any proved loss or`
  line `damage occasioned by the of fence of which he is convicted.`
  line `59. Review of p roceedings. — ( 1 ) In every case in which punishment has been awarded under`
  line `section 58, certified true copies of the proceedings shall be forwarded, in the prescribed manner, by the`
  line `officer awarding the punishment to the prescribed superior authority who may, if the punishment awarded`
  line `appears to him to be illegal, unjust or excessive, cancel, vary or remit the punishment and make such`
  line `other direction as may be appropriate in the circumstances of the case.`
  line `( 2 ) For the purpose of sub - section ( 1 ), a “superior authority” means, —`
  line `( a ) any officer superior in command to such officer who has awarded the punishment;`
  line `( b ) in the case of punishment awarded by Director - G eneral, the Central Government.`
  line `60. Collective fines. — ( 1 ) Whenever any weapon or part of a weapon, or ammunition, forming part of`
  line `the equipment of a unit, is lost or stolen, a commanding officer not below the rank of the Commandant of`
  line `that unit may, after making such enquiry as he thinks fit and subject to the rules, impose a collective fine`
  line `upon the subordinate officers, under - officers and men of such unit, or upon so many of them as, in his`
  line `judgment, should be held resp onsible for such loss or theft.`
  line `( 2 ) Such fine shall be assessed as a percentage of the pay of the individuals on whom it falls.`
  line `CHAPTER V`
  line `D EDUCTIONS FROM PAY AND ALLOWANCES`
  line `61. Deductions from pay and allowances of persons subject to this Act. — ( 1 ) The following`
  line `deductions may be made from the pay and allowances of an officer, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) all pay and allowances due to an officer for every day he absents himself without leave, unless`
  line `a satisfactory explanation has been given to, and accepted by, the Inspector - General under whom he`
  line `is for the time being serving;`
  line `( b ) all pay and allowances for every day while he is in custody on a charge for an offence for`
  line `which he is afterwards convicted by a criminal court or Force Court or by an officer exercis ing`
  line `authority under section 58;`
  line `( c ) any sum required to make good the pay of any person subject to this Act which he has`
  line `unlawfully retaine d or unlawfully refused to pay;`
  line `( d ) any sum required to make good such compensation for any expenses, loss, damage or`
  line `destruction occasioned by the commission of an offence as may be determined by the Force Court by`
  line `which he is convicted of such offence or by an officer exercis ing authority under section 58;`
  line `( e ) all pay and allowances or dered by Force Court;`
  line `( f ) any sum required to be paid as fine awarded by a c riminal court or a Force Court;`
  line `( g ) any sum required to make good any loss, damage or destruction of public or Force property`
  line `which, after due investig ation, appears to the Inspector - General under whom the officer is for the time`
  line `being serving, to have been occasioned by the wrongful act or neglige nce on the part of the officer;`
  line `( h ) all pay and allowances forfeited by order of the Central Government if the officer is found by`
  line `a court of inqu iry constituted by the Director - General in this behalf, to have deserted to the enemy, or`
  line `while in enemy hands, to have served with, or under the orders of, the enemy, or in any manner to`
obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_22:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-22
  sectionNo (22)
  orderNo 22
  title `Page 22`
  content obj_root_law_sections_22_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_22_footnotes
  sourcePage 22
obj_root_law_sections_22_content:
  string
  line 22
  line `have aided the enemy, or to have allowed himself to be taken prisoner by the enemy through want of`
  line `due precaution or through disobedience of orders or wilful neglect of duty, or having been taken`
  line `prisoner by the enemy, to have failed to rejoin his service when it was possible to do so;`
  line `( i ) any sum required by order of the Central Government to be paid for the maintenance of his`
  line `wife or his legitimate or illegitimate child or step child towards the cost of any relief given by the said`
  line `Govern ment to the said wife or child.`
  line `( 2 ) Subject to the provisions of section 63, the following deductions may be made from the pay and`
  line `allowances of a person subject to this Act, other than an officer, that is to say, —`
  line `( a ) all pay and allowances for every day of absence either on desertion or without leave, or as a`
  line `prisoner of war unless a satisfactory explanation has been given and accepted by his commanding`
  line `officer and for every day of imprisonment awarded by a criminal court, Force Court or an officer`
  line `exercis ing authority under section 56;`
  line `( b ) all pay and allowances for every day while he is in custody on a charge for an offence of`
  line `which he is afterwards convicted by a criminal court or Force Court or on a charge of absence without`
  line `leave for which he is afterwards awarded imprisonment by an officer exercising authority under`
  line `sec tion 56;`
  line `( c ) all pay and allowances for every day on which he is in hospital on account of sickness`
  line `certified by the medical officer attending on him to have been caused by an offence u nder this Act`
  line `committed by him;`
  line `( d ) for every day on which he is in hospital on account of sickness certified by the medical officer`
  line `attending on him to have been caused by his own misconduct or imprudence, such sum as may be`
  line `specified by the order of the Director - General;`
  line `( e ) all pay and allowances ordered by Force Court or by an officer exercising authority under any`
  line `of the sections 56 and 58 to be forfeited or stopped;`
  line `( f ) all pay and allowances for every day between his being recovered from the enemy and his`
  line `dismissal from the service in consequence of his conduct when being taken prisoner by, or w hile in`
  line `the hands of the enemy;`
  line `( g ) any sum required to make good such compensation for any expenses, loss, damage or`
  line `destruction caused by him to the Central Government or to any building or property or any private`
  line `fund of the Force as may be awa rded by his commanding officer;`
  line `( h ) any sum required to pay a fine awarded by a criminal court, Force Court exercising`
  line `jurisdiction under section 49 or an officer exercising authority under any of the sections 56 and 60;`
  line `( i ) any sum required by order of the Central Government or any prescribed officer to be paid for`
  line `the maintenance of his wife, or his legitimate child or illegitimate child or step child or towards the`
  line `cost of any relief given by the said Government to the said wife or c hild.`
  line `( 3 ) For computation of time of absence or custody under this section, —`
  line `( a ) no person shall be treated as absent or in custody for a day unless the absence or custody has`
  line `lasted, whether wholly in one day, or partly in one day and partly in another for si x consecutive hours`
  line `or upwards;`
  line `( b ) any absence or custody for less than a day may be reckoned as absence or custody for a day if`
  line `such absence or custody prevented the absentee from fulfilling any duty as member of the Force`
  line `which was thereby thrown u pon some other person;`
  line `( c ) absence or custody for twelve consecutive hours or upwards may be reckoned as absence or`
  line `custody for the whole of each day during any portion of which the p erson was absent or in custody;`
  line `( d ) a period of absence, or imprisonment, which commences before, and ends after, midnight may`
  line `be reckoned as a day.`
obj_root_law_sections_22_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_23:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-23
  sectionNo (23)
  orderNo 23
  title `Page 23`
  content obj_root_law_sections_23_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_23_footnotes
  sourcePage 23
obj_root_law_sections_23_content:
  string
  line 23
  line `62. Pay and allowances during trial. — In the case of any person subject to this Act who is in`
  line `custody or under suspension from duty on a charge for an offence, the prescribed officer may direct that`
  line `the whole or any part of the pay and allowances of such person shall be withheld, pending the result of his`
  line `trial on the charge against him, in order to give effect to the provisions of clause ( b ) of sub - sections ( 1 )`
  line `and ( 2 ) of section 61.`
  line `63. Limit of certain deductions. — The total deductions from the pay and allowances of a person`
  line `made under clauses ( e ) and ( g ) to ( i ) of sub - section ( 2 ) of section 61 shall not, except where he is`
  line `sentenced to dismissal or removal, exceed in any one month one - half of his pay an d allowances for that`
  line month.
  line `64. Deduction from public money due to a person. — Any sum authorised by this Act to be`
  line `deducted from the pay and allowances of any person may, without prejudice to any other mode of`
  line `recovering the same, be deducted from any public money due to him other than a pension.`
  line `65. Pay and allowances of prisoner of war during inquiry into his conduct. — Where the conduct`
  line `of any person subject to this Act when being taken prisoner by, or while in the hands of, the enemy, is to`
  line `be inquired into under this Act or any other law, the Director - General or any officer authorised by him`
  line `may order that the whole or any part of the pay and allowances of such person shall be withheld pend ing`
  line `the result of such enquiry.`
  line `66. Remission of deductions. — Any deduction from pay and allowances authorised by this Act may`
  line `be remitted in such manner and to such extent, and by such authority, as may from time to time be`
  line prescribed.
  line `67. Provision for dependents of prisoner of war from his remitted deductions and pay and`
  line `allowances. — ( 1 ) In the case of all persons subject to this Act, being prisoners of war, whose pay and`
  line `allowances have been forfeited under clause ( h ) of sub - section ( 1 ) or clause ( a ) of sub - section ( 2 ) of`
  line `section 61 but in respect of whom a remission has been made under section 66, it shall be lawful for`
  line `proper provisions to be made by the Central Government or by the Director - General when so authorised`
  line `by the Central Government out of such pay and allowances for any dependants of such persons and any`
  line `such remission shall in that case be deemed to apply only to the balance thereafter remain ing of such pay`
  line `and allowances.`
  line `( 2 ) It shall be lawful for proper provision to be made by the Central Government or by the`
  line `Director - General when so authorised by the Central Government for any dependants of any person`
  line `subject to this Act who is a prisoner of war, or is missing, out of his pay and allowances.`
  line `68. Period during which a person is deemed to be a prisoner of war. — For the p urposes of`
  line `section 67, a person shall be deemed to continue to be a prisoner of war until the conclusion of any`
  line `inquiry into his conduct such as is referred to in section 65 and if he is dismissed from the service in`
  line `consequence of such conduct, until the date of such dismissal.`
  line `CHAPTER VI`
  line `A RREST AND PROCEEDINGS BEFORE TRIAL`
  line `69. Custody of offenders. — ( 1 ) Any person subject to this Act who is charged with an offence may`
  line `be taken into Force custody under the order of any superior officer.`
  line `( 2 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub - section ( 1 ), an officer may order into Force custody`
  line `any other officer, though such other officer may be of a higher rank, engaged in a quarrel, affray or`
  line disorder.
  line `70. Duty of commanding o fficer in regard to detention. — ( 1 ) It shall be the duty of every`
  line `commanding officer to take care that a person under his command when charged with an offence is not`
  line `detained in custody for more than forty - eight hours after the committal of such person into custody is`
  line `reported to him, without the charge being investigated, unless investigation within that period seems to`
  line `him to be impracticable havin g regard to the public service.`
obj_root_law_sections_23_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_24:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-24
  sectionNo (24)
  orderNo 24
  title `Page 24`
  content obj_root_law_sections_24_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_24_footnotes
  sourcePage 24
obj_root_law_sections_24_content:
  string
  line 24
  line `( 2 ) The case of every person being detained in custody beyond a period of forty - eight hours, and the`
  line `reasons therefor, shall be reported by the commanding officer to the next higher officer or such other`
  line `officer to whom an application may be made to convene a Force Court for the tr i al of the person charged.`
  line `( 3 ) In reckoning the period of forty - eight hours specified in sub - section ( 1 ), S unday s and other pub lic`
  line `holidays shall be excluded.`
  line `( 4 ) Subject to the provisions of this Act, the Central Government may make rules providing for the`
  line `manner in which and the period for which any person subject to this Act may be taken into and detained`
  line `in Force custody, pending the trial by any competent authority for an y offence committed by him.`
  line `71. Interval between committal and trial. — In every case where any such person as is mentioned in`
  line `section 69 and as is not on active duty, remains in such custody for a longer period than eight days`
  line `without a Force Court for his trial being convened, a special report giving re a sons for the delay shall be`
  line `made by his commanding officer in the manner prescribed, and a similar report shall be forwarded at`
  line `intervals of every eight days until a Force Court is convened or such p erson is released from custody.`
  line `72. Arrest by civil authorities. — Whenever any person subject to this Act, who is accused of an`
  line `offence under this Act, is within the jurisdiction of any magistrate or police officer, such magistrate or`
  line `police officer shall aid in the apprehension and delivery to Force custody of such person upon receipt of a`
  line `written application to that effect signed by his commanding officer or an officer authorised by the`
  line `com manding officer in that behalf.`
  line `73. Capture of deserters. — ( 1 ) Whenever any person subject to this Act deserts, the commanding`
  line `officer of the unit to which he belongs or is attached, shall give information of the desertion to such civil`
  line `authorities as, in his opinion, may be able to afford assistance towards the capture of the deserter; and`
  line `such authorities shall thereupon take steps for the apprehension of the said deserter in like manner as if he`
  line `were a person for whose apprehension a warrant had been issued by a magistrate, and shall de liver the`
  line `deserter, when apprehen ded, into Force custody.`
  line `( 2 ) Any police officer may arrest without warrant any person reasonably believed to be subject to this`
  line `Act, and to be a deserter or to be travelling without authority, and shall bring him without delay before the`
  line `nearest magistrate, to be dealt with according to law.`
  line `74. Inquiry into absence without leave. — ( 1 ) When any person subject to this Act has been absent`
  line `from duty without due authority for a period of thirty days, a court of inquiry shall, as soon as practicable,`
  line `be appointed by such authority and in such manner as may be prescribed; and such court shall, on oath or`
  line `affirmation administered in the prescribed manner, inquire respecting the absence of the person, and the`
  line `deficiency, if any, in the property of the Government entrusted to his care, or in any arms, am munition,`
  line `equipment, instruments, clothing or necessaries; and if satisfied of the fact of such absence without due`
  line `authority or other sufficient cause, the court shall declare such absence and the period thereof and the said`
  line `deficiency, if any, and the commanding officer of the unit to which the person belongs or is attached,`
  line `shall make a record th ereof in the prescribed manner.`
  line `( 2 ) If the person declared absent does not afterwards surrender or is not apprehended, he shall, for the`
  line `purposes of this A ct, be deemed to be a deserter.`
  line `75. Force Police Officers. — ( 1 ) The Director - General or any prescribed officer may appoint persons`
  line `(in this Act referred to as Force Police) for discharging the functions specified in sub - sections ( 2 ) and ( 3 ).`
  line `( 2 ) The duties of a person appointed under sub - section ( 1 ) are to take charge of persons confined for`
  line `any offence, to preserve good order and discipline and to prevent breaches of the same by persons servin g`
  line `in, or attached to the Force.`
  line `( 3 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in section 69, a person appointed under sub - section ( 1 ) may,`
  line `at any time, arrest and detain for trial any person subject to this Act who commits, or is charged with, an`
  line `offence, and may also carry into effect any punishment to be inflicted in pursuance of a sentence awarded`
  line `by a Force Court or by an officer exercising authority under section 56 but shall not inf lict any`
  line `p unishment on his own authority:`
  line `Provided that no officer shall be so arrested or detained otherwise than on the order of another officer.`
obj_root_law_sections_24_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_25:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-25
  sectionNo (25)
  orderNo 25
  title `Page 25`
  content obj_root_law_sections_25_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_25_footnotes
  sourcePage 25
obj_root_law_sections_25_content:
  string
  line 25
  line `CHAPTER VII`
  line `F ORCE C OURTS`
  line `76. Kinds of Force Courts. — For the purposes of this Act there shall be three kinds of Force Courts,`
  line `that is to s ay, —`
  line `( a ) General Force Courts;`
  line `( b ) Petty Force Courts; and`
  line `( c ) Summary Force Courts.`
  line `77. Power to c onvene a General Force Court. — A General Force Court may be convened by the`
  line `Central Government or the Director - General or by any officer empowered in this beh alf by warrant of the`
  line `Director - General.`
  line `78. Power to Convene a Petty Force Court. — A Petty Force Court may be convened by an officer`
  line `having power to convene a General Force Court or by an officer empowered in this behalf by warrant of`
  line `any such officer.`
  line `79. Contents of warrants issued under sections 77 and 78. — A warrant issued under section 77 or`
  line `section 78 may contain such restrictions, reservations or conditions as the officer issuing it may think fit.`
  line `80. Composition of a General Force Court. — A General Force Court shall consist of not less than`
  line `five officers.`
  line `81. Composition of a Petty Force Court. — A Petty Force Court shall consist of not less than three`
  line `off icers.`
  line `82. Summary Force Court. — ( 1 ) A Summary Force Court may be held by the commanding officer`
  line `of any unit and he alone shall constitut e the Court.`
  line `( 2 ) The proceedings shall be attended throughout by two other persons who shall be officers or`
  line `subordinate officers or one of either, and who shall not as such, be sworn or affirmed.`
  line `83. Dissolution of a Force Court. — ( 1 ) If a Force Court after the commencement of a trial is reduced`
  line `below the minimum number of officers required by this Act, it shall be dissolved.`
  line `( 2 ) If, on account of the illness of the concerned Judge Attorney or, as the case may be, Deputy Judge`
  line `Attorney - General or Additional Judge Attorney - General or of the accused before the finding, it is`
  line `impossible to continue the trial, the Force Court shall be dissolved.`
  line `( 3 ) The authority or officer who convened a Force Court may dissolve the same if it appears to him`
  line `that the exigencies of the service or necessities of discipline render it impossible or inexpedient to`
  line `continue the said Force Court.`
  line `( 4 ) Where a Force Court is dissolved under this section, the accused may be tried again.`
  line `84. Power of a General Force Court. — A General Force Court shall have the power to try any`
  line `person subject to this Act for any offence punishable thereunder and to pass any sentence authorised`
  line thereby.
  line `85. Power of a Petty Force Court. — A Petty Force Court shall have the power to try any person`
  line `subject to this Act other than an officer or a subordinate officer for any offence made punishable`
  line `thereunder and to pass any sentence authorised by this Act other than a sentence of death or imprisonment`
  line `for a term exceeding two years.`
  line `86. Power of a Summary Force Court. — ( 1 ) Subject to the provisions of sub - section ( 2 ), a`
  line `Summary Force Court may try any offence punishable under th is Act.`
  line `( 2 ) When there is no grave reason for immediate action and reference can without detriment to`
  line `discipline be made to the officer empowered to convene a Petty Force Court for the trial of the alleged`
  line `offender, an officer holding a Summary Force Court shall not try without such reference any offence`
  line `punishable under any of the sections 16, 19 and 49, or any offence against the officer holding the Court.`
obj_root_law_sections_25_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_26:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-26
  sectionNo (26)
  orderNo 26
  title `Page 26`
  content obj_root_law_sections_26_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_26_footnotes
  sourcePage 26
obj_root_law_sections_26_content:
  string
  line 26
  line `( 3 ) A Summary Force Court may try any person subject to this Act and under the command of the`
  line `officer holding the Court, except an of ficer or a subordinate officer.`
  line `( 4 ) A Summary Force Court may pass any sentence which may be passed under this Act, except the`
  line `sentence of death or of imprisonment for a term exceeding the limit specified in sub - section ( 5 ).`
  line `( 5 ) The limit referred to in sub - section ( 4 ) shall be, —`
  line `( a ) one year, if the officer holding the Force Court holds the rank not below that of a`
  line Commandant;
  line `( b ) t hree months, in any other case.`
  line `87. Prohibition of second trial. — ( 1 ) When any person, subject to this Act has been acquitted or`
  line `convicted of an offence by a Force Court or by a criminal court or has been dealt with under section 56 or`
  line `section 58, he shall not be liable to be tried again for the same offence by a Force Court or deal t with`
  line `under the said sections.`
  line `( 2 ) When any person subject to this Act, has been acquitted or convicted of an offence by a Force`
  line `Court or has been dealt with under section 56 or section 58, he shall not be liable to be tried again by a`
  line `criminal court for the sam e offence or on the same facts.`
  line `88. Period of limitation for trial. — ( 1 ) Except as provided by sub - section ( 2 ), no trial by a Force`
  line `Court of any person subject to this Act for any offence shall be commenced after the expiration of a`
  line `period of three years from the date of such offence.`
  line `( 2 ) The provisions of sub - section ( 1 ) shall not apply to a trial for an offence of desertion or for any of`
  line `the of fences mentioned in section 19.`
  line `( 3 ) In the computation of the p eriod of time mentioned in sub - section ( 1 ), any time spent by such`
  line `person in evading arrest after the commission of the offence, shall be excluded.`
  line `89. Trial, etc., of offender who ceases to be subject to this Act. — ( 1 ) Where an offence under this`
  line `Act had been committed by any person while subject to this Act, and he has ceased to be so subject, he`
  line `may be taken into and kept in F orce custody and tried and punished for such offence as if he continued to`
  line `be so subject.`
  line `( 2 ) No such person shall be tried for an offence, unless his trial commences within six months after he`
  line `had ce ased to be subject to this Act:`
  line `Provided that nothing contained in this sub - section shall apply to the trial of any such person for an`
  line `offence of desertion or for any of the offences mentioned in section 19 or shall affect the jurisdiction of a`
  line `criminal court to try any offence triable by such cou rt as well as by a Force Court.`
  line `90. Application of Act during term of sentence. — ( 1 ) When a person subject to this Act is`
  line `sentenced by a Force Court to imprisonment, this Act shall apply to him during the term of his sentence,`
  line `though he is dismissed from the Force, or has otherwise ceased to be subject to this A ct, and he may be`
  line `kept, removed, imprisoned and punished as if he conti nued to be subject to this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) When a person subject to this Act is sentenced by a Force Court to death, this Act shall apply to`
  line `him till th e sentence is carried out.`
  line `91. Place of trial. — Any person subject to this Act who commits any offence against it may be tried`
  line `and punished for such offence in any place whatever.`
  line `92. Choice between criminal court and Force Court. — When a criminal court and a Force Court`
  line `have each jurisdiction in respect of an offence, it shall be in the discretion of the Director - General or the`
  line `Additional Director - General or the Inspector - General or the Deputy Inspector - General or the Additional`
  line `Deputy Inspector - General within whose command the accused person is serving or such other officer as`
  line `may be prescribed, to decide before which court the proce edings shall be instituted, and if that officer`
  line `decides that they shall be instituted before a Force Court, to direct that the accused person shal l be`
  line `detained in Force custody.`
obj_root_law_sections_26_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_27:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-27
  sectionNo (27)
  orderNo 27
  title `Page 27`
  content obj_root_law_sections_27_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_27_footnotes
  sourcePage 27
obj_root_law_sections_27_content:
  string
  line 27
  line `93. Power of criminal court to require delivery of offender. — ( 1 ) When a criminal court having`
  line `jurisdiction is of opinion that proceedings shall be instituted before itself in respect of any alleged`
  line `offence, it may, by written notice, require the officer referred to in section 92 at his option, either to`
  line `deliver over the offender to the nearest magistrate to be proceeded against according to law, or to`
  line `postpone proceedings, pending a refer ence to the Central Government.`
  line `( 2 ) In every such case the said officer shall either deliver over the offender in compliance with the`
  line `requisition, or shall forthwith refer the question as to the court before which the proceedings are to be`
  line `instituted, for the determination of the Central Government whose order upon such reference shall be`
  line final.
  line `CHAPTER VIII`
  line `P R OCEDURE OF F ORCE C OURTS`
  line `94. Presiding officer. — At every General Force Court or Petty Force Court, the senior member shall`
  line `be the presiding officer.`
  line `95. Judge Attorneys. — Every General Force Court shall, and every P etty Force Court may, be`
  line `attended by a Judge Attorney or a Deputy Judge Attorney - General or an Additional Judge`
  line `Attorney - General, or, if no such officer is available, an officer approved by the Judge Attorney - General or`
  line `by any officer authorised in this behalf by the Judge Attorney - General.`
  line `96. Challenge. — ( 1 ) At all trials by a General Force Court or by a Petty Force Court, as soon as the`
  line `Court is assembled, the names of the presiding officer and members shall be read over to the accused,`
  line `who shall thereupon be asked whether he objects to being tried by an y officer sitting on the Court.`
  line `( 2 ) If the accused objects to such officer, his objection and also the reply thereto of the officer`
  line `objected to shall be heard and recorded, and the remaining officers of the Court shall, in the absence of`
  line `the challenged o fficer decide on the objection.`
  line `( 3 ) If the objection is allowed by one - half or more of the votes of the officers entitled to vote, the`
  line `objection shall be allowed, and the member objected to shall retire, and his vacancy may be filled in the`
  line `prescribed manner, by another officer subject to the same right of the accused to object.`
  line `( 4 ) When no challenge is made, or when a challenge has been made and disallowed, or the place of`
  line `every officer successfully challenged has been filled by another officer to whom no objection is made or`
  line `allowed, the Cour t shall proceed with the trial.`
  line `97. Oaths of member, Judge Attorney and witness. — ( 1 ) An oath or affirmation in the prescribed`
  line `manner shall be administered to every member of the Force Court and to the Judge Attorney, or, as the`
  line `case may be, the Deputy Judge Attorney - General or the Additional Judge Attorney - General or the officer`
  line `approved under section 95, before the commencement of the trial.`
  line `( 2 ) Every person giving evidence before a Force Court shall be examined after being duly sworn or`
  line `a ffirmed in the prescribed form.`
  line `( 3 ) The provisions of sub - section ( 2 ) shall not apply where the witness is a child under twelve years`
  line `of age and the Force Court is of opinion that though the witness understands the duty of speaking the`
  line `truth, he does not understand the na ture of an oath or affirmation.`
  line `98. Voting by members. — ( 1 ) Subject to the provisions of sub - sections ( 2 ) and ( 3 ), every decision of`
  line `a Force Court shall be passed by an absolute majority of votes; and where there is an equality of votes on`
  line `either the finding or the sentence, the decision sha ll be in favour of the accused.`
  line `( 2 ) No sentence of death shall be passed by a General Force Court without the concurrence of at least`
  line `two - thir ds of the members of the Court.`
  line `( 3 ) In matters other than a challenge or the finding or sentence, the presiding officer shall have a`
  line `casting vote.`
  line `99. General rule as to evidence. — The Indian Evidence Act, 1872 (1 of 1872), shall, subject to the`
  line `provisions of this Act, apply to all pr oceedings before a Force Court.`
obj_root_law_sections_27_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_28:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-28
  sectionNo (28)
  orderNo 28
  title `Page 28`
  content obj_root_law_sections_28_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes
  sourcePage 28
obj_root_law_sections_28_content:
  string
  line 28
  line `100. Judicial notice. — A Force Court may take judicial notice of any matter within the general`
  line `knowledge of the me mbers as officers of the Force.`
  line `101. Summoning witnesses. — ( 1 ) The convening officer, the presiding officer of a Force Court, the`
  line `Judge Attorney or, as the case may be, the Deputy Judge Attorney - General or the Additional Judge`
  line `Attorney - General or the officer approved under section 95 or the C ommanding O fficer of the accused`
  line `person may, by summons under his hand, require the attendance, at a time and place to be mentioned in`
  line `the summons, of any person either to give evidence or to produ ce any document or other thing.`
  line `( 2 ) In the case of a witness who is subject to this Act or any other Act relating to the armed forces of`
  line `the Union, the summons shall be sent to his C ommanding O fficer and such officer shall serve it upon him`
  line accordingly.
  line `( 3 ) In the case of any other witness, the summons shall be sent to the magistrate within whose`
  line `jurisdiction he may be, or resides, and such magistrate shall give effect to the summons as if the witness`
  line `were required in the court of such a magistrate.`
  line `( 4 ) When a witness is required to produce any particular document or other thing in his possession or`
  line `power, the summons shall describ e it with reasonable precision.`
  line `102. Documents exempted from production. — ( 1 ) Nothing in section 101 shall be deemed to affect`
  line `the operation of sections 123 and 124 of the Indian Evidence Act, 1872 (1 of 1872) or to apply to any`
  line `letter, postcard, telegram or other document in the custody of the p ostal or telegraph authorities.`
  line `( 2 ) If any document in such custody is, in the opinion of any District Magistrate, Chief Metropolitan`
  line `Magistrate, Chief Judicial Magistrate, Court of Sessions or High Court wanted for the purpose of any`
  line `Force Court, such Magistrate or Court may require the postal or telegraph authorities, as the case may be,`
  line `to deliver such document to such person as such Magistrate or Court may direct.`
  line `( 3 ) If any such document is, in the opinion of any other magistrate or of any Commissioner of Police`
  line `or District Superintendent of Police, wanted for any such purpose, he may require the postal or telegraph`
  line `authorities, as the case may be, to cause such search to be made for, and to detain such document pending`
  line `the orders of any such District Magistrate, Chief Metropolitan Magistrate, Chief Judicial Magistrate,`
  line `C ourt of Sessions or High Court.`
  line `103. Commissions for examination of witnesses. — ( 1 ) Whenever, in the course of a trial by a Force`
  line `Court, it appears to the Court that the examination of a witness is necessary for the ends of justice, and`
  line `that the attendance of such witness cannot be procured without an amount of delay, expense or`
  line `inconvenience which, in the circumstances of the case, would be unreasonable, such Court may address`
  line `the Judge Attorney - General in order that a commission to take the evidence of such witness may be`
  line issued.
  line `( 2 ) The Judge Attorney - General may then, if he thinks necessary, issue a commission to any`
  line `Metropolitan Magistrate or Judicial Magistrate of the first class, within the local limits of whose`
  line `jurisdiction such witness resides, to tak e the evidence of such witness.`
  line `( 3 ) The Magistrate to whom the commission is issued, or, if he is the Chief Metropolitan Magistrate,`
  line `or Chief Judicial Magistrate, or such Metropolitan Magistrate, or Judicial Magistrate, as he appoints in`
  line `this behalf, shall summon the witness before him or proceed to the place where the witness is, and shall`
  line `take down his evidence in the same manner, and may for this purpose exercise the same powers, as in the`
  line `trials of warrant - cases under the Code of Crimin al Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `( 4 ) When the witness resides in a tribal area or in any place outside India, the commission may be`
  line `issued in the manner specified in Chapter XXIII of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `104. Examination of a witness on commission. — ( 1 ) The prosecutor and the accused person in any`
  line `case in which a commission is issued under section 103 may respectively forward any interrogatories in`
  line `writing which the court may think relevant to the issue, and the Magistrate executing the commission`
  line `shall examine the wit ness upon such interrogatories.`
obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_29:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-29
  sectionNo (29)
  orderNo 29
  title `Page 29`
  content obj_root_law_sections_29_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_29_footnotes
  sourcePage 29
obj_root_law_sections_29_content:
  string
  line 29
  line `( 2 ) The prosecutor and the accused person may appear before such Magistrate by counsel, or, except`
  line `in the case of an accused person in custody, in person, and may examine, cross - examine, and re - examine,`
  line `as the case may be, the said witness.`
  line `( 3 ) After a commission issued under section 103 has been duly executed, it shall be returned together`
  line `with the deposition of the witness examined thereunder to the Judge Attorney - General.`
  line `( 4 ) On receipt of a commission and deposition returned under sub - section ( 3 ), the Judge`
  line `Attorney - General shall forward the same to the Court at whose instance the commission was issued or, if`
  line `such Court has been dissolved, to any other Court convened for the trial of the accused person; and the`
  line `commission, the return thereto and the deposition shall be open to inspection by the prosecutor and the`
  line `accused person, and may, subject to all just exceptions, be read in evidence in the case by either the`
  line `pr osecutor or the accused, and shall form part o f the proceedings of the Court.`
  line `( 5 ) In every case in which a commission is issued under section 103, the trial may be adjourned for`
  line `specified time reasonably sufficient for the executio n and return of the commission.`
  line `105. Conviction for offences not charged. — A person charged before a Force Court —`
  line `( a ) with desertion may be found guilty of attempting to desert or of being absent without leave;`
  line `( b ) with attempting to desert may be found guilty of being absent without leave;`
  line `( c ) with using criminal force may be found guilt y of assault;`
  line `( d ) with using threatening language may be found guilty of us ing insubordinate language;`
  line `( e ) with any one of the offences specified in clauses ( a ), ( b ), ( c ) and ( d ) of section 33 may be`
  line `found guilty of any other of these offences with whi ch he might have been charged;`
  line `( f ) with an offence punishable under section 49 may be found guilty of any other offence of`
  line `which he might have been found guilty, if the provisions of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 197 3`
  line `(2 of 1974), were applicable;`
  line `( g ) with any offence under this Act may, on failure of proof of an offence having been committed`
  line `in circumstances involving a more severe punishment, be found guilty of the same offence as having`
  line `been committed in circumstances involving a less severe punishment;`
  line `( h ) with any offence under this Act may be found guilty of having attempted or abetted the`
  line `commission of that offence, although the attempt or abet ment is not separately charged.`
  line `106. Presumption as to signatures. — In any proceeding under this Act, any application, certificate,`
  line `warrant, reply or other document purporting to be signed by an officer in the service of the Government`
  line `shall, on production, be presumed to have been duly signed by the person by whom and in the character in`
  line `which it purports to have been signe d, until the contrary is shown.`
  line `107. Enrolment paper. — ( 1 ) Any enrolment paper purporting to be signed by an enrolling officer`
  line `shall, in proceedings under this Act, be evidence of the person enrolled having given the answers to`
  line `questions which he is there in represented as having given.`
  line `( 2 ) The enrolment of such person may be proved by the production of the original or a copy of his`
  line `enrolment paper purporting to be certified to be a true copy by the officer having the custody of the`
  line `enr olment paper or service record.`
  line `108. Presumption as to certain documents. — ( 1 ) A letter, return or other document respecting the`
  line `service of any person in, or the dismissal, removal or discharge of any person from, any unit of the Force,`
  line `or respecting the circumstances of any person not having served in, or belonged to, any unit of the Force,`
  line `if purporting to be signed by or on behalf of the Central Government or the Director - General, or by any`
  line `prescribed officer, shall be evidence of the facts stated in such le tter, return or other documen t.`
  line `( 2 ) A Force List or Gazette purporting to be published by authority shall be evidence of the status and`
  line `rank of the officers, subordinate officers therein mentioned, and of any appointment held by them and of`
  line `the battalion, unit, or branch of the Force to which they belong.`
obj_root_law_sections_29_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_30:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-30
  sectionNo (30)
  orderNo 30
  title `Page 30`
  content obj_root_law_sections_30_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_30_footnotes
  sourcePage 30
obj_root_law_sections_30_content:
  string
  line 30
  line `( 3 ) Where a record is made in any battalion book in pursuance of this Act or of any rules made`
  line `thereunder or otherwise in the discharge of official duties, and purports to be signed by the commanding`
  line `officer or by the officer whose duty it is to make such record, such record shall be eviden ce of the facts`
  line `therein stated.`
  line `( 4 ) A copy of any record in any office of the Force purporting to be certified to be a true copy by the`
  line `officer having custody of such book shall be evidence of such record.`
  line `( 5 ) Where any person subject to this Act is being tried on a charge of desertion or of absence without`
  line `leave, and such person has surrendered himself into the custody of any officer or other person subject to`
  line `this Act, or any unit of the Force, or has been apprehended by such officer or person, a certificate`
  line `purporting to be signed by such officer, or by the commanding officer of the unit to which such person`
  line `belongs or is attached, as the case may be, and stating the fact, date and place of such surrender or`
  line `apprehension, and the manner in which he was dressed, shall be evi dence of the matters so stated.`
  line `( 6 ) Where any person subject to this Act is being tried on a charge of desertion or of absence without`
  line `leave and such person has surrendered himself into the custody of, or has been apprehended by, a police`
  line `officer not below the rank of an officer in charge of a police station, a certificate purporting to be signed`
  line `by such police officer and stating the fact, date and place of such surrender or apprehension and the`
  line `manner in which he was dressed shall be evid ence of the matters so stated.`
  line `( 7 ) ( a ) Any document purporting to be a report under the hand of a Government scientific expert to`
  line `whom this sub - section applies, upon any matter or thing duly submitted to him for examination or`
  line `analysis and report in the course of any proceeding under this Act, may be used as evidence in any`
  line `inquiry, trial or other proceeding under this Act.`
  line `( b ) The Force Court may, if it thinks fit, summon and examine any such expert as to th e subject`
  line `matter of his report.`
  line `( c ) Where any such expert is summoned by a Force Court and he is unable to attend personally, he`
  line `may, unless the Court has expressly directed him to appear personally, depute an officer who is`
  line `conversant with the facts of the case to dep ose in the Court on his behalf.`
  line `( d ) This sub - section applies to the Government scientific experts, for the time being specified in`
  line `sub - section ( 4 ) of section 293 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 197 3 (2 of 1974 ).`
  line `109. Reference by accused to Government officer. — ( 1 ) If at any trial for desertion or absence`
  line `without leave, over - staying leave or not rejoining when warned for service, the accused person states in`
  line `his defence any sufficient or reasonable excuse for his unauthorised absence, and refers in support thereof`
  line `to any officer in the service of the Government, or if it appears that any such officer is likely to prove or`
  line `disprove the said statement in the defence, the Court shall address such officer and adjourn th e`
  line `proceedin gs until his reply is received.`
  line `( 2 ) The written reply of any officer so referred to shall, if signed by him, be received in evidence and`
  line `have the same effect as if made on oath before the Court.`
  line `( 3 ) If the court is dissolved before the receipt of such reply or if the Court omits to comply with the`
  line `provisions of this section, the convening officer may, at his discretion, annul the proceedings and order a`
  line `fresh trial.`
  line `110. Evidence of previous convictions and general character. — ( 1 ) When any person subject to`
  line `this Act has been convicted by a Force Court of any offence, such Force Court may inquire into, and`
  line `receive, and record evidence of any previous convictions of such person, either by a Force Court or by a`
  line `criminal court, or any previous award of punishment under section 56 or section 58, and may further`
  line `inquire into and record the general character of such person and such other ma tters as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 2 ) Evidence received under this section may be either oral, or in the shape of entries in, or certified`
  line `extracts from, books of Force Courts or other official records; and it shall not be necessary to give notice`
  line `before trial to the person tried that evidence as to his previous convictions or character will be received.`
obj_root_law_sections_30_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_31:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-31
  sectionNo (31)
  orderNo 31
  title `Page 31`
  content obj_root_law_sections_31_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_31_footnotes
  sourcePage 31
obj_root_law_sections_31_content:
  string
  line 31
  line `( 3 ) At a summary Force Court, the officer holding the trial may, if he thinks fit, record any previous`
  line `convictions against the offender, his general character, and such other matters as may be prescribed, as of`
  line `his own knowledge, instead of requiring them to be proved under the foregoing provisions of this section.`
  line `111. Lunacy of accused. — ( 1 ) Whenever, in the course of a trial by a Force Court, it appears to the`
  line `Court that the person charged is by reason of unsoundness of mind incapable of making his defence, or`
  line `that he committed the act alleged but was by reason of unsoundness of mind incapable of knowing the`
  line `nature of the act or knowing that it was wrong or contrary to law, the Court shal l record a finding`
  line accordingly.
  line `( 2 ) The presiding officer of the Court, or, in the case of a Summary Force Court, the officer holding`
  line `the trial, shall forthwith report the case to the confirming officer, or to the authority empowered to deal`
  line `with its finding under s ection 129, as the case may be.`
  line `( 3 ) The confirming officer to whom the case is reported under sub - section ( 2 ) may, if he does not`
  line `confirm the finding, take steps to have the accused person tried by the same or another Force Court for the`
  line `off ence with which he was charged.`
  line `( 4 ) The authority to whom the finding of a Summary Force Court is reported under sub - section ( 2 )`
  line `and a confirming officer confirming the finding in any case so reported to him shall order the accused`
  line `person to be kept in custody in the prescribed manner and shall report the case for the or ders of the`
  line `Central Government.`
  line `( 5 ) On receipt of a report under sub - section ( 4 ), the Central Government may order the accused`
  line `person to be detained in a lunatic asylum or other suitable place of safe custody.`
  line `112. Subsequent fitness of lunatic accused for trial. — Where any accused person, having been`
  line `found by reason of unsoundness of mind to be incapable of making his defence, is in custody or under`
  line `detention under section 111, any officer prescribed in this behalf, may —`
  line `( a ) if such person is in custody under sub - section ( 4 ) of section 111, on the report of a medical`
  line `officer that he is ca pable of making his defence, or`
  line `( b ) if such person is detained in a jail under sub - section ( 5 ) of section 111, on a certificate of the`
  line `Inspector - General of P risons, and if such person is detained in a lunatic asylum under the said`
  line `sub - section, on a certificate of any two or more of the visitors of such asylum and if he is detained in`
  line `any other place under that sub - section, on a certificate of the prescribed authority, that he is capable`
  line `of making his defence,`
  line `take steps to have such person tried by the same or another Force Court for the offence with which he was`
  line `originally charged or, if the offence is a civil offence, by a criminal court.`
  line `113. Transmission to Central Government of orders under section 112. — A copy of every order`
  line `made by an officer under section 112 for the trial of the accused shall forthwith be sent to the Central`
  line Government.
  line `1 14. Release of lunatic accused. — Where any person is in custody under sub - section ( 4 ) of`
  line `section 111 or under detention under sub - section ( 5 ) of that section, —`
  line `( a ) if such person is in custody under the said sub - section ( 4 ), on the report of a medical officer,`
  line or
  line `( b ) if such person is detained under the said sub - section ( 5 ), on a certificate from any of the`
  line `authorities mentioned in clause ( b ) of section 112 that in the judgment of such officer or authority`
  line `such person may be released without danger of his doing injury to himself or to any other person,`
  line `the Central Government may order that such person be released or detained in custody or transferred to a`
  line `public lunatic asylum if he has not alrea dy been sent to such an asylum.`
  line `115. Delivery of lunatic accused to relatives. — Where any relative or friend of any person who is in`
  line `custody under sub - section ( 4 ) of section 111 or under detention under sub - section ( 5 ) of that section`
  line `desires that he should be delivered to his care and custody, the Central Government may, upon application`
  line `by such relative or friend and, on his giving security to the satisfaction of that Government that the person`
obj_root_law_sections_31_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_32:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-32
  sectionNo (32)
  orderNo 32
  title `Page 32`
  content obj_root_law_sections_32_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_32_footnotes
  sourcePage 32
obj_root_law_sections_32_content:
  string
  line 32
  line `delivered shall be properly taken care of, and, prevented from doing injury to himself or to any other`
  line `person, and be produced for the inspection of such officer, and at such times and places, as the Central`
  line `Government may direct, order such person to be delive red to such relative or friend.`
  line `116. Order for custody and disposal of property pending trial. — When any property regarding`
  line `which any offence appears to have been committed, or which appears to have been used for the`
  line `commission of any offence, is produced before a Force Court during a trial, the Court may make such`
  line `order as it thinks fit for the proper custody of such property pending the conclusion of the trial, and if the`
  line `property is subject to speedy or natural decay may, after recording such evidence as it thinks necessary,`
  line `order it to be sold or otherwise disposed of.`
  line `117. Order for disposal of property regarding which offence is committed. — ( 1 ) After the`
  line `conclusion of a trial before any Force Court, the Court or the officer confirming the finding or sentence of`
  line `such Force Court, or any authority superior to such officer, or, in the case of a Summary Force Court`
  line `whose finding or sentence does not require confirmation, an officer not below the rank of Additional`
  line `Deputy Inspector - General within whose command the trial was held, may make such order as it or he`
  line `thinks fit for the disposal by destruction, confiscation, delivery to any person claiming to be entitled to`
  line `possession thereof, or otherwise, of any property or document produced before the Court or in its custody,`
  line `or regarding which any offence appears to have been committed or which has been used for the`
  line `commission of any offence.`
  line `( 2 ) Where any order has been made under sub - section ( 1 ) in respect of property regarding which an`
  line `offence appears to have been committed, a copy of such order signed and certified by the authority`
  line `making the same may, whether the trial was held within India or not, be sent to a magistrate within whose`
  line `jurisdiction such property for the time being is situated, and such magistrate shall thereupon cause the`
  line `order to be carried into effect as if it were an order passed by him under the provisions of the Code of`
  line `Crimin al Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `( 3 ) In this section, the term “property” includes, in the case of property regarding which an offence`
  line `appears to have been committed, not only such property as has been originally in the possession or under`
  line `the control of any person, but also any property into or for which the same may have been converted or`
  line `exchanged, and anything acquired by such conversion or exchange whether immediately or otherwise.`
  line `118. Powers of Force Court in relation to proceedings under this Act. — Any trial by a Force`
  line `Court under the provisions of this Act shall be deemed to be a judicial proceeding within the meaning of`
  line `sections 193 and 228 of the Indian Penal Code (45 of 1860) and the Force Court shall be deemed to be a`
  line `court within the meaning of sections 345 and 346 of the C ode of Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `119. Tender of pardon to accomplies. — ( 1 ) With a view to obtaining the evidence of any person`
  line `supposed to have been directly or indirectly concerned in or privy to an offence triable by a Force Court`
  line `other than a Summary Force Court under this Act, the commanding officer, the convening officer or the`
  line `Force Court, at any stage of the investigation or inquiry into or the trial of, the offence, may tender a`
  line `pardon to such person on condition of his making a full and true disclosure of the whole of the`
  line `circumsta nces within his knowledge relating to the offence and to every other person concerned, whether`
  line `as principal or abet tor, in the commission thereof.`
  line `( 2 ) The commanding officer or the convening officer who tenders a pardon under sub - section ( 1 )`
  line `shall record —`
  line `( a ) his reasons for so doing;`
  line `( b ) whether the tender was or was not accepted by the person to whom it was made,`
  line `and shall, on application made by the accused, furnish him with a co py of such record free of cost.`
  line `( 3 ) Every person accepting a tend er of pardon made under sub - section ( 1 ) —`
  line `( a ) shall be examined as a witness by the commanding officer of the accused and i n the`
  line `subsequent trial, if any;`
  line `( b ) may be detained in Force custody unti l the termination of the trial.`
obj_root_law_sections_32_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_33:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-33
  sectionNo (33)
  orderNo 33
  title `Page 33`
  content obj_root_law_sections_33_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_33_footnotes
  sourcePage 33
obj_root_law_sections_33_content:
  string
  line 33
  line `120. Trial of person not complying with conditions of pardon. — ( 1 ) Where, in regard to a person`
  line `who has accepted a tender of pardon made under section 119, the Judge Attorney, or as the case ma y be,`
  line `the Deputy Judge Attorney - General or the Additional Judge Attorney - General or the officer approved`
  line `under section 95, certifies that in his opinion such person has, either by wilfully concealing anything`
  line `essential or by giving false evidence, not complied with the conditions on which the tender was made,`
  line `such person may be tried for the offence in respect of which the pardon was so tendered or for any other`
  line `offence of which he appears to have been guilty in connection with the same matter, and also for the`
  line `of fence of giving false ev idence:`
  line `Provided that such person shall not be tried jointly with any of the other accused.`
  line `( 2 ) Any statement made by such person accepting the tender of pardon and recorded by his`
  line `commanding officer o r Force Court may be given in evid ence against him at such trial.`
  line `( 3 ) At such trial, the accused shall be entitled to plead that he has complied with the condition upon`
  line `which such tender was made; in which case it shall be for the prosecution to prove that the condit ion has`
  line `not been complied with.`
  line `( 4 ) At such trial, the Force Court shall, before arraignment, ask the accused whether he pleads that he`
  line `has complied with the conditions on which the tender of pardon was made.`
  line `( 5 ) If the accused does so plead, the Court shall record the plea and proceed with the trial and it shall,`
  line `before giving its finding on the charge, find whether or not the accused has complied with the conditions`
  line `of the pardon, and, if it finds that he has so complied, it shall give a verdict of not guilty.`
  line `CHAPTER IX`
  line `C ONFIRMATION AND REVISION`
  line `121. Finding and sentence not valid unless confirmed. — No finding or sentence of a General Force`
  line `Court or a Petty Force Court shall be valid except so far as it may be confirmed as provided by this Act.`
  line `122. Power to confirm finding and sentence of General Force Court. — The findings and sentences`
  line `of General Force Courts may be confirmed by the Central Government or by any officer empowered in`
  line `this behalf by war rant of the Central Government.`
  line `123. Power to confirm finding and sentence of Petty Force Court. — The findings and sentences of`
  line `a Petty Force Court may be confirmed by an officer having power to convene a General Force Court or by`
  line `any officer empowered in this beh alf by warrant of such officer.`
  line `124. Limitation of powers of confirming authority. — A warrant issued under section 122 or`
  line `section 123 may contain such restrictions, reservations or conditions as the authority issuing it may think`
  line fit.
  line `125. Power of confirming authority to mitigate, remit or commute sentences. — Subject to such`
  line `restrictions, reservations or conditions, as may be contained in any warrant issued under section 122 or`
  line `section 123, a confirming authority may, when confirming the sentence of a Force Court, mitigate or`
  line `remit the punishment thereby awarded or commute that punishment for any punishment or punishments`
  line `lower in the scale laid down in section 51.`
  line `126. Confirming of findings and sentences on board a ship. — When any person subject to this Act`
  line `is tried and sentenced by a Force Court while on board a ship, the finding and sentence so far as not`
  line `confirmed and executed on board the ship, may be confirmed and executed in like manner as if such`
  line `person had been tried at the port of disembarkation.`
  line `127. Revision of finding o r sentence. — ( 1 ) Any finding or sentence of a Force Court which requires`
  line `confirmation may be once revised by order of the confirming authority and on such revision, the Court, if`
  line `so directed by the confirming authority, may take additional evidence.`
  line `( 2 ) The Court, on revision, shall consist of the same officers as were present when the original`
  line `decision was passed unless any of those o fficers are unavoidably absent.`
obj_root_law_sections_33_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_34:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-34
  sectionNo (34)
  orderNo 34
  title `Page 34`
  content obj_root_law_sections_34_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_34_footnotes
  sourcePage 34
obj_root_law_sections_34_content:
  string
  line 34
  line `( 3 ) In case of such unavoidable absence the cause thereof shall be duly certified in the proceedings,`
  line `and the Court shall proceed with the revision, provided that, if a General Force Court, it still consists of`
  line `five officers, or, if a P etty Force Court, of three officers.`
  line `128. Finding and sentence of a Summary Force Court. — The finding and sentence of a Summary`
  line `Force Court shall not require to be confirmed, bu t may be carried out forthwith.`
  line `129. Transmission of proceedings of Summary Force Court. — The proceedings of every Summary`
  line `Force Court shall, without delay be forwarded to the officer not below the rank of Additional Deputy`
  line `Inspector - General within whose command the trial was held, or to the prescribed officer, and such officer,`
  line `or the Director - General or any officer empowered by him in this behalf may, for reasons based on the`
  line `merits of the case, but not on merely technical grounds, set aside the proceedings, or reduce the sentence`
  line `to any other sentence whi ch the Court might have passed.`
  line `130. Alteration of finding or sentence in certain cases. — ( 1 ) Where a finding of guilty by a Force`
  line `Court, which has been confirmed or which does not require confirmation, is found for any reason to be`
  line `invalid or cannot be supported by the evidence, the authority which would have had power under`
  line `section 142 to commute the punishment awarded by the sentence, if the finding had been valid may`
  line `substitute a new finding and pass a sentence for the offence specified or involved in such finding:`
  line `Provided that no such substitution shall be made unless such finding could have been validly made by`
  line `the Force Court on the charge and unless it appears that the Force Court must have been satisfied of the`
  line `facts establishing the said offence.`
  line `( 2 ) Where a sentence passed by a Force Court which has been confirmed, or which does not require`
  line `confirmation, not being a sentence passed in pursuance of a new finding substituted under sub - section ( 1 ),`
  line `is found for any reason to be invalid, the authority referred to in sub - section ( 1 ) may pass a valid`
  line sentence.
  line `( 3 ) The punishment awarded by a sentence passed under sub - section ( 1 ) or sub - section ( 2 ) shall not`
  line `be higher in the scale of punishments than, or in excess of, the punishment awarded by, the sentence for`
  line `which a new sentence is substituted under this section.`
  line `( 4 ) Any finding substituted, or any sentence passed, under this section shall, for the purposes of this`
  line `Act and the rules, have effect as if it were a finding or sentence, as the case may be, of a Force Court.`
  line `1 31. Remedy against order, finding or sentence of Force Court. — ( 1 ) Any person subject to this`
  line `Act who considers himself aggrieved by any order passed by any Force Court may present a petition to`
  line `the officer or authority empowered to confirm any finding or sentence of such Force Court, and the`
  line `confirming authority may take such steps as may be considered necessary to satisfy itself as to the`
  line `correctness, legality or propriety of the order passed or as to the regularity of any proceed ing to which the`
  line `order re lates.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person subject to this Act who considers himself aggrieved by a finding or sentence of any`
  line `Force Court which has been confirmed, may present a petition to the Central Government, the Director -`
  line `General or any prescribed officer superior in command to the one who conf irmed such finding or`
  line `sentence, and the Central Government, the Director - General, or the prescribed officer, as the case may be,`
  line `may pass such order thereon as it or he thinks fit.`
  line `132. Annu lment of proceedings. — The Central Government, the Director - General or any prescribed`
  line `officer may annul the proceedings of any Force Court on the ground that they are illegal or unjust.`
  line `CHAPTER X`
  line `E XECUTION OF SENTENCES, PARDONS, REMISSIONS, ETC.`
  line `133. Form of sentence of death. — In awarding a sentence of death, a Force Court shall, in its`
  line `discretion direct that the offender shall suffer death by being hanged by the neck until he be dead, or shall`
  line `suffer death by being shot to death.`
obj_root_law_sections_34_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_35:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-35
  sectionNo (35)
  orderNo 35
  title `Page 35`
  content obj_root_law_sections_35_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_35_footnotes
  sourcePage 35
obj_root_law_sections_35_content:
  string
  line 35
  line `134. Commencement of sentence of imprisonment. — Whenever any person is sentenced by a Force`
  line `Court under this Act to imprisonment, the term of his sentence shall, whether it has been revised or not,`
  line `be reckoned to commence on the day on which the original proceedings were signed by the presiding`
  line `officer, or in the case of a Sum mary Force Court, by the Court:`
  line `Provided that —`
  line `( i ) if for any reason, beyond the control of the commanding officer or superior officer, the`
  line `sentence of imprisonment cannot be executed in full or in part, the convict shall be liable to undergo`
  line `the whole or unexpired portion of sentence, as the case may be, when it becomes poss ible to carry out`
  line `the same;`
  line `( ii ) the period of detention or confinement, if any, undergone by an accused person, during the`
  line `investigation, inquiry or trial of the case in which he is sentenced and before the date on which the`
  line `original proceedings were signed shall be set off against the term of his sentence and the liability of`
  line `such person to undergo imprisonment shall be restricted to the remainder, if a ny of the term of his`
  line sentence.
  line `135. Execution of sentence of imprisonment. — ( 1 ) Whenever any sentence of imprisonment is`
  line `passed under this Act by a Force Court or whenever any sentence of death is commuted to imprisonment,`
  line `the confirming officer or in case of a Summary Force Court the officer holding the Court or such other`
  line `officer as may be prescribed shall, save as otherwise provided in sub - sections ( 3 ) and ( 4 ), direct that the`
  line `sentence shall be carried out by confinement in a civil prison.`
  line `( 2 ) When a direction has been made under sub - section ( 1 ), the commanding officer of the person`
  line `under sentence or such other officer as may be prescribed shall forward a warrant in the prescribed form`
  line `to the officer in charge of the prison in which such person is to be confined and shall arrange for his`
  line `dispatch t o such prison with the warrant.`
  line `( 3 ) In the case of a sentence of imprisonment for a period not exceeding three months and passed`
  line `under this Act by a Force Court, the appropriate officer under sub - section ( 1 ) may direct that the sentence`
  line `shall be carried out by confinement in Force custod y instead of in a civil prison.`
  line `( 4 ) On active duty, a sentence of imprisonment may be carried out by confinement in such place as`
  line `the officer not below the rank of Additional Deputy Inspector - General within whose command the person`
  line `sentenced is serving or any prescribed officer may from time to time appoint.`
  line `136. Temporary custody of offender. — Where a sentence of imprisonment is directed to be`
  line `undergone in a civil prison, the offender may be kept in Force custody or in any other fit place till such`
  line `time as it is possible to send him to a civil prison.`
  line `137. Execution of sentence of imprisonment in special cases. — Whenever, in the opinion of an`
  line `officer not below the rank of Additional Deputy I nspector - General within whose command the trial is`
  line `held, any sentence or portion of a sentence of imprisonment cannot for special reasons conveniently be`
  line `carried out in Force custody in accordance with the provisions of section 135, such officer may direct that`
  line `such sentence or portion of sentence shall be carried out by confinement in any c ivil prison or other fit`
  line `pla ce.`
  line `138. Conveyance of prisoner from place to place. — A person under sentence of imprisonment may`
  line `during his conveyance from place to place, or when on board a ship, aircraft, or otherwise, be subjected to`
  line `such restraint as is necessary fo r his safe conduct and removal.`
  line `139. Communication of certain orders to prison officers. — Whenever an order is duly made under`
  line `this Act setting aside or varying any sentence, order or warrant under which any person is confined in a`
  line `civil prison, a warrant in accordance with such order shall be forwarded by the officer making the order or`
  line `his staff officer or such other person as may be prescribed, to the officer in charge of the prison in which`
  line `such person is confined.`
obj_root_law_sections_35_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_36:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-36
  sectionNo (36)
  orderNo 36
  title `Page 36`
  content obj_root_law_sections_36_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes
  sourcePage 36
obj_root_law_sections_36_content:
  string
  line 36
  line `140. Execution of sentence of fine. — When a sentence of fine is imposed by a Force Court under`
  line `section 49, a copy of such sentence signed and certified by the confirming officer, or where no`
  line `confirmation is required, by the officer holding the trial may be sent to any magistrate in India, and such`
  line `magistrate shall thereupon cause the fine to be recovered in accordance with the provisions of the Code of`
  line `Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974), as if it were a sentence of fine imposed by such magistrate.`
  line `141. Informality or error in the order or warrant. — Whenever any person is sentenced to`
  line `imprisonment under this Act, and is undergoing the sentence in any place or manner in which he might be`
  line `confined under a lawful order or warrant in pursuance of this Act, the confinement of such person shall`
  line `not be deemed to be illegal only by reason of informality or error in, or as respects, the order, warrant or`
  line `other document, or the authority by which, or in pursuance whereof such person was brought into, or, is`
  line `conf ined in any such place, and any such order, warrant or document may be amended accordingly.`
  line `142. Pardon and remission. — When any person subject to this Act has been convicted by a Force`
  line `Court of any offence, the Central Government or the Director - General or, in the case of a sentence, which`
  line `he could have confirmed or which did not require confirmation, an officer not below the rank of`
  line `Additional Deputy Inspector - General within whose command such person at the time of conviction was`
  line `serving, or the prescribed officer may, —`
  line `( a ) either with or without conditions which the person sentenced accepts, pardon the person or`
  line `remit the whole or any part of the punishments awarded; or`
  line `( b ) mitigate the punishment awarded; or`
  line `( c ) commute such punishment for any less punishment or punishments mentioned in this Act; or`
  line `( d ) either with or without conditions which the person sentenced accepts, release the person on`
  line parole.
  line `143. Cancellation of conditional pardon, release on parole or remission. — ( 1 ) If any condition on`
  line `which a person has been pardoned or released on parole or a punishment has been remitted is, in the`
  line `opinion of the authority which granted the pardon, release or remission, not fulfilled, such authority may`
  line `cancel the pardon, release or remission, and thereupon the sentence of the Court shall be carried into`
  line `effect as if such pardon, release or remission had not been granted.`
  line `( 2 ) A person whose sentence of imprisonment is carried into effect under the provisions of`
  line `sub - section ( 1 ) shall undergo only the unexp ired portion of his sentence.`
  line `144. Suspension of sentence of imprisonment. — ( 1 ) Where a person subject to this Act is sentenced`
  line `by a Force Court to imprisonment, the Central Government, the Director - General or any officer`
  line `empowered to convene a General Force Court may suspend the sentence whether or not the offender has`
  line `already been committed to prison or to Force custody.`
  line `( 2 ) The authority or officer specified in sub - section ( 1 ) may, in the case of an offender so sentenced`
  line `direct that until the orders of such authority or officer have been obtained, the offender shall not be`
  line `committed to prison or to Force custody.`
  line `( 3 ) The powers conferred by sub - sections ( 1 ) and ( 2 ) may be exercised in the case of any such`
  line `sentence which has been confirmed, reduced or commuted.`
  line `145. Orders pending suspension. — ( 1 ) Where the sentence referred to in section 144 is imposed by`
  line `a Force Court other than a summary Force Court, the confirming officer may, when confirming the`
  line `sentence, direct that the offender be not committed to prison or to Force custody until the orders of the`
  line `authority or officer specified in section 144 have been obtained.`
  line `( 2 ) Where a sentence of imprisonment is imposed by a Summary Force Court, the officer holding the`
  line `trial may make the direction referred to in sub - section ( 1 ).`
  line `146. Release on suspension. — Where a sentence is suspended under section 144, the offender shall`
  line `forthwith be released from custody.`
obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_37:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-37
  sectionNo (37)
  orderNo 37
  title `Page 37`
  content obj_root_law_sections_37_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_37_footnotes
  sourcePage 37
obj_root_law_sections_37_content:
  string
  line 37
  line `147. Computation of period of suspension. — Any period during which the sentence is under`
  line `suspension shall be reckoned as par t of the term of such sentence.`
  line `148. Order after suspension. — The authority or officer specified in section 144 may, at any time`
  line `while a sentence is suspended, order —`
  line `( a ) that the offender be committed to undergo the unexpi red portion of the sentence; or`
  line `( b ) that the sentence be remitted.`
  line `149. Reconsideration of case after suspension. — ( 1 ) Where a sentence has been suspended, the case`
  line `may at any time, and shall at intervals of not more than four months, be reconsidered by the authority or`
  line `officer not below the rank of an Additional Deputy Inspector - General duly authorised by the authority or`
  line `of ficer specified in section 144.`
  line `( 2 ) Where on such reconsideration by the officer so authorised it appears to him that the conduct of`
  line `offender since his conviction has been such as to justify a remission of the sentence, he shall refer the`
  line `matter to the authority or of ficer specified in section 144.`
  line `150. Fresh sentence after suspension. — Where an offender, while a sentence on him is suspended`
  line `under this Act, is sentenced for any other offence, then —`
  line `( a ) if the further sentence is also suspended under this Act, the two sentences shall run`
  line concurrently;
  line `( b ) if the further sentence is for a period of three months or for and is not suspended under this`
  line `Act, the offender shall also be committed to prison or Force custody for the unexpired portion of the`
  line `previous sentence, but both senten ces shall run concurrently; and`
  line `( c ) if the further sentence is for a period of less than three months and is not suspended under this`
  line `Act, the offender shall be so committed on that sentence only, and the previous sentence shall, subject`
  line `to any order which may be passed under section 148 or section 149, continue to be suspended.`
  line `151. Scope of power of suspension. — The powers conferred by sections 144 and 148 shall be in`
  line `addition to, and not in derogation of, the power of mitigation, remission and commutation.`
  line `152. Effect of suspension and remission on dismissal. — ( 1 ) Where in addition to any other sentence`
  line `the punishment of dismissal has been awarded by a Force Court, and such other sentence is suspended`
  line `under section 144, then, such dismissal shall not take effect until so ordered by the authority or of ficer`
  line `specified in section 144.`
  line `( 2 ) If such other sentence is remitted under section 148, the punishment of di smissal shall also be`
  line remitted.
  line `CHAPTER XI`
  line `M ISCELLANEOUS`
  line `153. Rank structure. — ( 1 ) The officers and other members of the Force shall be classified in`
  line `accordance with their ranks in the following categ ories, namely: —`
  line `( a ) officers —`
  line `( i ) Director - General.`
  line `( i i ) Additional Director - General.`
  line `( iii ) Inspector - General.`
  line `( iv ) Deputy Inspector - General.`
  line `( v ) Addit ional Deputy Inspector - General.`
  line `( vi ) Commandant.`
  line `( vii ) Second - in - Command.`
obj_root_law_sections_37_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_38:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-38
  sectionNo (38)
  orderNo 38
  title `Page 38`
  content obj_root_law_sections_38_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_38_footnotes
  sourcePage 38
obj_root_law_sections_38_content:
  string
  line 38
  line `( viii ) Deputy Commandant.`
  line `( ix ) Assistant Commandant.`
  line `( b ) subordinate officers —`
  line `( i ) Subedar - Major.`
  line `( ii ) Subedar/Inspector.`
  line `( iii ) Sub - Inspector.`
  line `( c ) under officers —`
  line `( i ) Head Constable.`
  line `( ii ) Naik.`
  line `( iii ) Lance naik.`
  line `( d ) enrolled persons other than under officers — constable.`
  line `( 2 ) The matters relating to inter se seniority of persons belonging to the same rank shall be`
  line `determined in accordance with s uch rules as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 3 ) Notwithstanding anything conta ined in this Act, the Director - General may, subject to`
  line `confirmation of the Central Government as provided hereinafter, grant to an officer or a Subedar - Major of`
  line `the Force a rank, mentioned in clause ( a ) of sub - section ( 1 ) as a local rank, whenever considered`
  line `necessary by him in the interest of b etter functioning of the Force.`
  line `( 4 ) An officer of t he Force holding a local rank, —`
  line `( a ) shall exercise the command and be vested with the powers o f an officer holding that rank;`
  line `( b ) shall cease to hold that rank if the grant of such rank is not confirmed within one month by the`
  line `C entral Government or when so ordered by the Director - General or when he ceases to hold the`
  line `appointment for which the rank was granted;`
  line `( c ) shall not be entitled to claim any seniority over other officers of the Force by virtu e of having`
  line `held such rank; and`
  line `( d ) shall not be entitled to any extra pay and al lowances for holding such rank.`
  line `Explanation I. — Assistant Commandant shall also include a J oint Assistant Commandant in case of`
  line `personnel belonging to cadres of Motor Mechanic, Combatant Ministerial and Comba tant Stenographer of`
  line `the Force.`
  line `Explanation II. — Sub - Inspector shall include an Assistant Sub - Inspector in case of personnel`
  line `belonging to Combatant Ministerial cadre of the Force.`
  line `154. Powers and duties conferrable and imposable on members of the Force. — ( 1 ) The Central`
  line `Government may, by general or special order published in the Official Gazette, direct that, subject to such`
  line `conditions and limitations as may be specified in the order, any member of the Force may exercise or`
  line `discharge such of the powers or duties under any Central Act as may be specified in the said order, being`
  line `the powers and duties which, in the opinion of the Central Government, an officer of the corresponding or`
  line `lower rank is by such Central Act empowered to exercise or d ischarge for the said purposes.`
  line `( 2 ) The Central Government may, by general or special order published in the Official Gazette, confer`
  line `or impose, with the concurrence of the State Government concerned, any of the powers or duties which`
  line `may be exercised or discharged under a State Act by a police officer upon a member of the Force who, in`
  line `the opinion of the Central Government, holds a corresponding or higher rank.`
  line `( 3 ) Every order made under this section shall be laid, as soon as may be after it is made, before each`
  line `House of Parliament, while it is in session, for a total period of thirty days which may be comprised in`
  line `one session or in two or more successive sessions and if, before the expiry of the session immediately`
  line `following the session or the successive sessions aforesaid, both Houses agree in making any modification`
obj_root_law_sections_38_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_39:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-39
  sectionNo (39)
  orderNo 39
  title `Page 39`
  content obj_root_law_sections_39_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_39_footnotes
  sourcePage 39
obj_root_law_sections_39_content:
  string
  line 39
  line `in the order or both Houses agree that the order should not be made, the order shall thereafter have effect`
  line `only in such modified form or be of no effect, as the case may be; so, however, that any such modification`
  line `or annulment shall be without prejudice to the validity of anything pr eviously done under that order.`
  line `155. Protection for acts of members of the Force. — ( 1 ) In any suit or proceeding against any`
  line `member of the Force for any act done by him in pursuance of a warrant or order of a competent authority,`
  line `it shall be lawful for him to plead that such act was done by him under the auth ority of such warrant or`
  line order.
  line `( 2 ) Any such plea may be proved by the production of the warrant or order directing the act, and if it`
  line `is so proved the member of the Force shall thereupon be discharged from liability in respect of the act so`
  line `done by him, notwithstanding any defect in the jurisdiction of the authority whic h issued such warrant or`
  line order.
  line `( 3 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in any other law for the time being in force, any legal`
  line `proceeding (whether civil or criminal) which may lawfully be brought against any member of the Force`
  line `for anything done or intended to be done under the powers conferred by, or in pursuance of any provision`
  line `of this Act or the rules, shall be commenced within three months after the act complained of was`
  line `committed and not otherwise, and notice in writing of such proceeding and of the cause thereof shall be`
  line `given to t he defendant or his superior officer at least one month before the c ommencement of such`
  line proceeding.
  line `156. Power to make rules. — ( 1 ) The Central Government may, by notification, make rules for the`
  line `purpose of carrying into eff ect the provisions of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) In particular, and without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing power, such rules may`
  line `provide for —`
  line `( a ) the constitution, governance, comma nd and discipline of the f orce;`
  line `( b ) the enrolment of persons to the Force and the recruitment of other members of the Force;`
  line `( c ) the conditions of service (including deductions from pay and allow ances) of members of the`
  line Force;
  line `( d ) the precedence, powers of command and authority of the officers, subordinate officers,`
  line `under - officers and oth er persons subject to this Act;`
  line `( e ) the dismissal, removal, retirement, release or discharge from the service of persons subject to`
  line `this Act;`
  line `( f ) the purposes and other matters required to be prescribed under section 13;`
  line `( g ) the amount and incidence of fine to be imposed under section 60;`
  line `( h ) the convening, constitution, adjournment, dissolution and sittings of Force Courts, the`
  line `procedure to be observed in trials by such Courts, the persons by whom an accused may be defended`
  line `in such trials and the appe arance of such persons thereat;`
  line `( i ) the confirmation, revision and annulment of, and petitions against, the findings and sentences`
  line `of Force Courts;`
  line `( j ) the forms of orders to be made under the provisions of this Act relating to Force Courts and`
  line `the awards and infliction of death, imprisonment and detenti on;`
  line `( k ) the constitution of authorities to decide for what persons, to what amounts and in what`
  line `manner, provisions should be made for dependants under section 67 and the due carr ying out of such`
  line decisions;
  line `( l ) the carrying into effect of sentences of F orce Courts;`
  line `( m ) any matter necessary for the purpose of carrying this Act into execution, as far as it relates to`
  line `the investigation, arrest, custody, trial and punishment of offences triabl e or punishable under this`
  line Act;
obj_root_law_sections_39_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_40:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-40
  sectionNo (40)
  orderNo 40
  title `Page 40`
  content obj_root_law_sections_40_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_40_footnotes
  sourcePage 40
obj_root_law_sections_40_content:
  string
  line 40
  line `( n ) the ceremonials to be observed and marks of r espect to be paid in the Force;`
  line `( o ) the convening of, the constitution, procedure and practice of, courts of inquiry, the`
  line `summoning of witnesses before them and the administ ration of oaths by such courts;`
  line `( p ) the recruitment and conditio ns of service of J udge Attorney - General, Additional J udge`
  line `Attorney - General, Deputy Judge Attor ney - General and Judge Attorney;`
  line `( q ) the disposal of the private or regimental property, or any other dues including provident fund`
  line `of persons subject to this Act who die or desert or are ascertained to be of unsound mind or while on`
  line `active duty are officially reported as missing;`
  line `( r ) any other matter which is to be, or may be, prescribed, or in respect of which provision is t o`
  line `be, or may be, made by rules.`
  line `( 3 ) Every rule made under this Act shall be laid, as soon as may be after it is made, before each House`
  line `of Parliament, while it is in session, for a total period of thirty days which may be comprised in one`
  line `session or in two or more successive sessions, and if, before the expiry of the session immediately`
  line `following the session or the s u ccessive sessions aforesaid, both Houses agree in making any modification`
  line `in the rule or both Houses agree that the rule should not be made, the rule shall thereafter have ef fect only`
  line `in such modified form or be of no effect, as the case may be; so, however, that any such modification or`
  line `annulment shall be without prejudice to the validity of anything p reviously done under that rule.`
  line `157. Provisions as to existing I ndo - Tibetan Border Police Force. — ( 1 ) The Indo - Tibetan Border`
  line `Police Force in existence at the commencement of this Act shall be deemed to be the Fo rce constituted`
  line `under this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) The members of the Indo - Tibetan Border Police Force in existence at the commencement of this`
  line `Act shall be deemed to have been appointed or, as the case may be, e nrolled as such under this Act.`
  line `( 3 ) Anything done or any action taken before the commencement of this Act in relation to the`
  line `constitution of the Indo - Tibetan Border Police Force referred to in sub - section ( 1 ), in relation to any`
  line `person appointed or enrolled, as the case may be, thereto, shall be as valid and as effective in law as if`
  line `such thing or action was done or taken under this Act:`
  line `Provided that nothing in this sub - section shall render any person guilty of any offence in respect of`
  line `anything done or omitted to be done by him before the commencement of this Act.`
obj_root_law_sections_40_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_41:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-41
  sectionNo (41)
  orderNo 41
  title `Page 41`
  content obj_root_law_sections_41_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_41_footnotes
  sourcePage 41
obj_root_law_sections_41_content:
  string
  line 41
  line `STATEMENT OF OBJECTS AND REASONS`
  line `The Indo - Tibetan Border Police was raised in October, 1962. It is since then under operation. This`
  line `Force has been charged with the responsibility of ensuring the security of n o r thern border, instilling a`
  line `sense of security among the people living in the bor der areas and preventing tra ns - bord e r crimes,`
  line `smuggling and unauthorised ent r y into or exist from India territory in co - o rdina t or wi th other security`
  line `Forces. In addition, t h e Force has been assigned bank security duties and other sensitive duties in terrorist`
  line `afflicted States, However, considering the nature and purpo se of t he force and experience gained during`
  line `t he last three decades it ha s b ee n felt that the Force should be regulated by a separate self - contained`
  line `statute which will provide for its special needs, especially the needs of efficiency and discipline. The`
  line `present Bill seeks to achieve this object.`
  line `As the Indo - Tibetan Border Police Force is charged with the policing of the Northern borders, the Bill`
  line `seeks to ensure that the standards of efficiency and discipline of the Force are of a high order.`
  line `3. The Notes on clauses explain in brief the various provisions of the Bill.`
  line `S.B. CHAVAN.`
obj_root_law_sections_41_footnotes:
  string
  line
